/* The cross-tale layer — eight tales side by side.
   Annotates the same call-numbers across Culhwch, Pwyll, Branwen, Manawydan, Math, Owain, Orfeo and Gawain
   so the comparative payoff of the annotation stack becomes visible at a
   glance. Three tables: shared motifs (Thompson codes), shared Propp
   functions (with absences flagged where present), and shared character
   archetypes. Loaded after data.js; attaches to window.PENDRAGON. */
window.PENDRAGON = window.PENDRAGON || {};
window.PENDRAGON.crosswalk = {
  intro: "With nine poems now in the same apparatus — Culhwch ac Olwen (Welsh, c. 1100), the complete Four Branches of the Mabinogi (Pwyll, Branwen, Manawydan and Math, Welsh, manuscripts c. 1350–1410, story-stratum older), Owain neu Iarlles y Ffynnon (Welsh, one of the Three Welsh Romances), Sir Orfeo (Middle English, c. 1300), Sir Gawain and the Green Knight (Middle English, c. 1380), and Geoffrey of Monmouth’s Vita Merlini (Latin, c. 1150) — the comparative layer the motif index and the story graph open up can do its work. Below: the same Thompson Motif codes laid against all nine poems, the same Propp functions laid against all nine, and a small map of character archetypes that recur across them. Where a code is present in multiple tales the cross-reference is given; where it is sharply absent from one and central to another, the absence is named. Nine tales gives the comparative pattern real traction: six Welsh, two Middle English, and one Latin — and the Latin one, the <em>Vita Merlini</em>, is the deep-mythic outlier: it bends the wonder-tale spine almost out of recognition (its hero flees society, his quest is inward, his cure is given not won, his crown refused), yet it is the taproot the whole hub reaches for, the earliest home of Avalon, Morgen, and the once-and-future king. The Four Branches now stand complete in the grid (and are read together as a single work, with their own historiography, at the <a href=\"/mabinogi/\">Mabinogi</a> hub) — Owain, the Welsh twin of Chrétien’s Yvain, adds the Welsh↔Continental transmission question. The Branches make a four-cornered study in the same spine: Pwyll's exchanges and courtesy; Branwen, the corpus’s one tragedy, running the wonder-tale shape backwards into ruin (with the canonical talking head, E783, that Gawain later echoes); Manawydan completing the spine cleanly — a wasteland made whole — and closing the revenge-arc Pwyll opened (the badger-in-the-bag, K1601); and Math, the most magic-driven of all, where the engine is not a quest but transformation and trickery, worked by a single wand.",
  tales: [
    { id: "culhwch", title: "Culhwch ac Olwen",                short: "Culhwch", sigil: "🐗", href: "/culhwch/", color: "#7fb37f" },
    { id: "pwyll",   title: "Pwyll Pendefig Dyfed",            short: "Pwyll",   sigil: "🐎", href: "/pwyll/",   color: "#d8b24a" },
    { id: "branwen", title: "Branwen ferch Llŷr",                short: "Branwen", sigil: "🐦", href: "/branwen/", color: "#7f8fb3" },
    { id: "manawydan", title: "Manawydan uab Llŷr",             short: "Manawydan", sigil: "🐭", href: "/manawydan/", color: "#9d82b3" },
    { id: "math",    title: "Math uab Mathonwy",                short: "Math",    sigil: "🦉", href: "/math/",    color: "#56a0a0" },
    { id: "owain",   title: "Owain, neu Iarlles y Ffynnon",     short: "Owain",   sigil: "🦁", href: "/owain/",   color: "#c9854a" },
    { id: "orfeo",   title: "Sir Orfeo",                       short: "Orfeo",   sigil: "🎵", href: "/orfeo/",   color: "#6fa8c9" },
    { id: "gawain",  title: "Sir Gawain and the Green Knight", short: "Gawain",  sigil: "🪓", href: "/gawain/",  color: "#c97f9a" },
    { id: "vitamerlini", title: "Vita Merlini", short: "Vita Merlini", sigil: "🔮", href: "/vitamerlini/", color: "#6c63c9" },
  ],

  motifIntro: "Thompson Motif codes laid against the nine poems. Sorted by how many tales carry each: the codes at the top form the small structural backbone the poems share. (The <em>Vita Merlini</em> joins at the level of the deep Celtic Otherworld motifs — the wild man, the Isle of Apples, the triple death, the disguise-trick — rather than the romance-specific ones, so its column is sparse but pointed.) The codes at the bottom (single-tale) show what each poem brings uniquely into the comparison.",
  motifs: [
    // ── In all three ─────────────────────────────────────────────────
    { code: "M223", name: "The rash promise / blank check",
      culhwch: { passages: [2], note: "Arthur grants whatever Culhwch will name (save a reserved few treasures) before he hears the request." },
      pwyll:   { passages: [4], note: "Pwyll at the wedding feast grants Gwawl <em>“whatever you ask of me”</em> unheard — and Gwawl asks for the feast and Rhiannon. Rhiannon then turns the same form back on Gwawl with the bag-trick." },
      gawain:  { passages: [1, 3], note: "Arthur accepts the Green Knight's terms unheard; Bertilak's exchange-of-winnings struck on the same form." },
      orfeo:   { passages: [5], note: "Fairy King: <em>now aske of me what it be — largelich Ichil the pay; now speke, and tow might asay.</em> The hinge of the rescue." },
      owain: false,
      branwen: false,
      manawydan: { passages: [6], note: "Inverted and turned to the hero's advantage: cornered, the disguised Llwyd cries <em>“name your own price”</em> for the mouse's life — a blank cheque offered to Manawydan, who spends it clause by clause (the captives, the land, no revenge). The rash-boon form, with the villain forced to grant it." },
      gloss: "The single most ecumenical motif in the set. All four poems run on the rash boon — promise asked in the fairest possible form and then leveraged: in Culhwch to set the quest, in Pwyll to lose Rhiannon and then to recover her, in Gawain to extract the year-and-a-day, in Orfeo to recover the queen. Owain is the telling exception (a dash here): it runs not on a boon rashly granted but on a marriage-term solemnly given and then broken — the same binding word, seen from the side of its breach." },

    { code: "Z71.1", name: "Formulistic number: three",
      culhwch: { passages: [2, 7, 10], note: "Three shouts at Arthur's gate; three poisoned spears thrown back at Ysbaddaden; the boar Twrch hunted by Arthur and his men across three countries." },
      pwyll:   { passages: [3], note: "Three days of the chase on the Gorsedd Arberth — runner, fastest horseman, Pwyll himself; only the third asking halts Rhiannon. Three years of barren marriage before the men of Dyfed petition. Six women's lie pivots a third-night vigil." },
      gawain:  { passages: [1, 3, 4], note: "Three blows at the chapel, three hunts, three temptations, three exchanges of winnings, three days, three kisses. Z71.1 is pervasive." },
      orfeo:   { passages: [3, 5], note: "Three apparitions of the fae (hunt, host, dance); three laments; three harpings (wild beasts, Fairy King's court, the steward's hall). More sparing than Gawain." },
      owain: { passages: [5, 6, 8], note: "Three years holding the fountain; the three-day duel with Gwalchmei; the threefold sigh that reveals Luned in the dark — plus the three ridings to the fountain (Cynon, Owain, Arthur\u2019s company)." },
      branwen: { passages: [6], note: "The three Birds of Rhiannon sing over the assembly of the Wondrous Head; the colophon counts the Three Unhappy Blows of Britain (the box on Branwen\u2019s ear among them). But the branch leans as much on other formulistic tallies \u2014 the seven survivors, the fourscore years at Gwales, the five pregnant women left in Ireland \u2014 as on the triad." },
      manawydan: { passages: [3, 5, 6], note: "The most thoroughly triadic of the Branches: three crafts in England (saddles, shields, shoes), three crofts of wheat, three nights of mice, three visitors to the gallows (scholar, priest, bishop). The fairy-tale triple structures the whole second half." },
      math: { passages: [2, 4, 6], note: "Three years of beast-punishment in three shapes (deer, boar, wolves) with three beast-sons; Aranrhod's three curses (name, arms, wife); the three englynion that call the eagle down. The triple structures the whole branch." },
      vitamerlini: { passages: [1, 4, 6], note: "The triad runs through the whole poem — the three brothers slain, the threefold death, the boy shown three times, the three laughs." },
      gloss: "All eight lean on triadic structure, with sharply different densities (Owain keeps a steady triple beat: three years, three-day duel, threefold sigh). Gawain is built triadically at every level; Orfeo uses the three in selected places; Pwyll uses it once with great precision on the Gorsedd; Culhwch lets the threes share space with nines and other formulistic numbers." },

    { code: "A186", name: "Demoted divinity walking as character",
      culhwch: { passages: [8, 9], note: "Mabon son of Modron — \"Divine Son\" of \"Divine Mother\" — the British god Maponos demoted to imprisoned heir. Gwyn ap Nudd, king of Annwn." },
      pwyll:   { passages: [1, 3], note: "The whole tale runs on this. Arawn, lord of Annwn; Rhiannon as <em>Rigantona</em>, the Great Queen, with Epona's horse and bird signatures; Pryderi's theft-and-recovery as a Mabon-type. Pwyll is the locus classicus of Welsh god-as-character." },
      gawain:  { passages: [4], note: "Morgan le Fay named \"Morgne the goddess\" by Bertilak at the reveal; the Green Knight with his vegetation-god iconography." },
      orfeo:   { passages: [1, 2, 5], note: "Pluto and Juno named as Orfeo's ancestors, immediately glossed: <em>that sum time were as godes y hold</em> — were <em>held</em> for gods. The Fairy King allowed to stand as <em>king o fairy</em> without Christian framing." },
      owain: { passages: [2], note: "The keeper of beasts \u2014 the one-eyed, one-footed lord of the wild animals that bow to him \u2014 is an old nature-power demoted to a wood-warden; and Owain himself, in the wider tradition, is son of Modron (the goddess Matrona) and master of the Flight of Ravens named in the colophon." },
      branwen: { passages: [1, 6], note: "The whole House of Ll\u0177r is demoted divinity walking as kings: Br\u00e2n the Blessed, the sovereignty-giant whose buried head guards Britain; Manawydan, the Welsh reflex of the Irish sea-god Manann\u00e1n mac Lir; their father Ll\u0177r (Lir) the sea; and the Birds of Rhiannon (Rigantona) singing over the head\u2019s timeless feast. Like Pwyll, Branwen runs on old gods as characters without ever flagging them." },
      manawydan: { passages: [1, 6], note: "The House of Llŷr again: Manawydan is the Welsh reflex of the Irish sea-god Manannán mac Lir, son of Llŷr (Lir, the sea); Rhiannon is Rigantona, the demoted horse-goddess of the First Branch; and the adversary Llwyd is a magician of the old order. Like Pwyll and Branwen, the branch runs on demoted gods as plain kings and lords, never flagging the older weight." },
      math: { passages: [1, 4], note: "The other divine house: the children of Dôn (Gwydion, Gilfaethwy, Aranrhod, Gofannon) are the Welsh Túatha Dé Danann, the kindred of the goddess Dôn (= Irish Danu); Lleu Llaw Gyffes is the Welsh reflex of the pan-Celtic Lugus (Irish Lugh); Aranrhod survives in the star-name Caer Arianrhod. The whole branch runs on old gods walking as magicians and kings, never once flagged — the densest mythological substratum of the corpus alongside Pwyll." },
      vitamerlini: { passages: [9], note: "Morgen, the herb-wise healer-enchantress of the Isle of Apples, read as a demoted goddess — the Modron/Matrona behind the later 'Morgan le Fay'." },
      gloss: "Each poem manages older divinity differently. Culhwch lets old gods walk as heroes (Mabon's mythological lineage is part of his power). Pwyll runs an entire branch on demoted gods without ever flagging it — Arawn and Rhiannon are simply the king and the lady, and the audience is expected to feel the older weight. Gawain names Morgan a goddess as part of the unmasking. Orfeo opens by euhemerising Pluto and Juno explicitly — and then lets the Fairy King retain divine dignity under a different name. Owain keeps the oldest figure of all walking in plain sight — the keeper of beasts, the lord of animals demoted to a wood-warden. Manawydan, like Pwyll and Branwen, runs the House of Llŷr (Manannán, Rigantona) as plain kings and lords without flagging them; Math runs the other divine house, the children of Dôn, and Lleu the Welsh Lugus, the same way. Pwyll's silence is the most archaic handling of the eight, but Math's is the most thoroughly mythological — two whole divine families walking as one cast." },

    { code: "F252", name: "The Otherworld and its court",
      culhwch: { passages: [8], note: "Annwn and its lord Gwyn ap Nudd, demanded for the hunt; behind the whole tradition stands Avalon." },
      pwyll:   { passages: [2], note: "The canonical onstage Welsh Otherworld court. Annwn rendered as a fully-furnished Welsh medieval great hall with queen, courtiers, hounds, feast and protocol; Pwyll spends a year inside it ruling. Where Culhwch and Orfeo show Annwn from outside, Pwyll shows it from the throne." },
      gawain:  { passages: [2, 3, 4], note: "Hautdesert as Morgan's court of enchantment — Bertilak, the lady, the ancient lady, the household." },
      orfeo:   { passages: [2, 3, 4, 5], note: "A hundred snow-white knights and a hundred milk-white damsels; the Fairy King and Queen on thrones in a tabernacle of light; porter, courtiers, the half-taken." },
      owain: { passages: [2, 3, 4], note: "The fountain\u2019s domain \u2014 the storm-spring, the keeper, the lavish castle whose service no mortal court matches, the gold-imaged painted chamber \u2014 is an Otherworld-touched court naturalised in the Welsh manner (cf. Pwyll\u2019s Annwn), never flagged as fae." },
      branwen: { passages: [6], note: "Not a fairy court but the timeless feast at Gwales: the seven survivors and Br\u00e2n\u2019s undecayed head feast fourscore years out of time, untouched by age or sorrow, while the forbidden door stays shut \u2014 the Insular \u2018time stands still\u2019 Otherworld enclave, a court held past death itself." },
      vitamerlini: { passages: [9], note: "The Isle of Apples: Morgen and her nine sisters, the Otherworld court that receives the wounded Arthur as host and physician." },
      gloss: "All six stage an Otherworld court, with sharply different distances. Culhwch's is offstage — Annwn invoked, Gwyn drafted. Gawain's is hidden in plain sight as a Christmas castle. Orfeo's is the most fully imagined visually — crystal walls, ever-light, the yard of the half-taken. Pwyll's is the most fully <em>inhabited</em>: he rules it for a year, feasts with its queen, fights its civil war. Owain adds a fifth: the fountain-domain, Otherworldly in its marvels but presented as a mortal court, in the naturalising Welsh manner. Six distances on the same court — Branwen’s being the feast at Gwales, a court held out of time." },

    { code: "N825.3", name: "Old person as helper at the threshold",
      culhwch: { passages: [4, 5], note: "Custennin the fire-breathing herdsman and his wife (Culhwch's aunt by marriage), who hide Goreu in a stone chest and warn the company of the giant's terms." },
      pwyll:   { passages: [6], note: "Teirnon Twrf Liant — <em>the best man in the world</em>, the old story says — keeps and raises the stolen child in his stable-court for years, then recognises him and brings him to Pwyll. The faithful threshold-keeper of the recognition arc." },
      gawain:  { passages: [2, 3, 4], note: "The \"auncian lady\" beside the young wife at Hautdesert — Morgan le Fay in age-disguise, honoured at table without ever being recognised." },
      orfeo:   { passages: [6], note: "The Winchester beggar at the town's edge, in his narrow hut. Houses Orfeo and Heurodis, tells the city's news, lends the borrowed clothes." },
      owain: { passages: [2, 3, 6], note: "The threshold-helper is the keeper of beasts \u2014 monstrous rather than aged \u2014 who directs each questing knight to the fountain. Owain fills the aged-helper slot with a wild guardian, not an old man." },
      branwen: false,
      gloss: "An aged figure at the threshold turns out to hold the key in each tale. Moral colouring varies: Custennin's wife and Teirnon are helpers, the beggar is a quiet host, Morgan is the prime mover of the test. Same structural slot, five different moral occupants — the helper, the keeper-of-the-lost-child, the harmless witness, the disguised antagonist, the monstrous wood-warden who directs but does not aid (Owain), and — in Branwen — no aged helper at all, the role falling to a hand-reared starling (see the archetype grid)." },

    { code: "F151.1", name: "Perilous path to the Otherworld",
      culhwch: { passages: [4], note: "The fortress that comes no closer however long you walk — the Otherworld holding its distance." },
      pwyll:   false,
      gawain:  { passages: [2], note: "The wild road through North Wales and the Wirral — wolves, wodwos, ice in the armour, the Christmas Eve prayer." },
      orfeo:   { passages: [4], note: "Three miles through solid stone in a rock-cleft. Orfeo spares neither stub nor stone." },
      owain: false,
      branwen: false,
      vitamerlini: { passages: [9], note: "The sea-road to the Isle of Apples, sailed with Barinthus 'to whom the waters and the stars were known' — the passage to the Otherworld over water." },
      gloss: "Three different terrain-shapes for the same motif — and sharply absent from the Welsh prose tales Pwyll, Owain and Branwen. The Welsh tradition uses the unreachable fort (Culhwch); the Gawain-poet's tradition uses the winter wilderness ride; Orfeo uses the cleft-in-the-rock. Pwyll's Annwn has no perilous path because Arawn brings Pwyll there as a guest — the Otherworld is entered by invitation, not by ordeal. The tale of host-substitution refuses the threshold-as-trial." },

    { code: "H1556", name: "Test of fidelity",
      culhwch: { passages: [8, 9, 10, 11], note: "The impossible tasks of the anoethau test Culhwch (in fact Arthur) and his band — by completing every one, faithfulness to the bargain is proved." },
      pwyll:   { passages: [2], note: "The chaste-bed: Pwyll in Arawn's form sleeps a year beside Arawn's queen and turns his back every night, saying nothing. The clean structural test of marital fidelity-by-bargain — the one beat that earns him the name Pen Annwn." },
      gawain:  { passages: [3], note: "The exchange-of-winnings — three days of paralleled hunts and bedroom encounters. The test of whether the guest will give back honestly all he gained. Gawain passes twice; fails once, by a hand's-breadth." },
      orfeo:   { passages: [6], note: "Inverted — the hero tests the steward. The lying tale of his death; the steward's total grief; the conditional reveal." },
      owain: { passages: [6, 7], note: "The central test \u2014 and the only one in the corpus the hero FAILS: the marriage-term Owain swears and overstays. His broken fidelity is the hinge of the whole back half; Luned\u2019s fidelity to him (imprisoned for vouching) and the lion\u2019s are its answer." },
      branwen: false,
      manawydan: { passages: [4], note: "The pledge to Cigfa: alone with his stepson's wife in the emptied land, Manawydan swears on God to keep faith with the absent Pryderi and with her — and does. A fidelity-test passed quietly, and a direct rhyme with Pwyll's chaste-bed (his father-in-law keeping faith in Arawn's bed)." },
      gloss: "Six of the eight poems revolve around a test of loyalty (Owain alone has a hero who FAILS his — the broken term — and must win his way back). The position of hero is different in each: Culhwch as the tested party in absence (Arthur and the band test for him); Pwyll as the tested party in another man's bed; Gawain as the tested party in person at his host's bed; Orfeo as the testing party against his own servant. Three bedside tests of three different forms of fidelity — to bargain, to host, to absent queen — and one chamber-emptied test of fidelity-by-quest. Branwen has no fidelity-trial at all — its engine is a broken alliance and a villainy, though faith and its betrayal saturate it (Branwen’s endurance, Efnisien’s redeeming death)." },

    // ── In multiple ─────────────────────────────────────────────────
    { code: "F156", name: "Door to the Otherworld at a marked place",
      culhwch: false,
      pwyll:   { passages: [3], note: "The Gorsedd Arberth — a real burial-mound just above Pwyll's court. The old custom: whatever nobleman sits on it suffers a hurt or sees a marvel. Pwyll sits there deliberately and Rhiannon comes." },
      gawain:  { passages: [4], note: "The Green Chapel turns out to be a hollow grass-grown barrow with three openings, beside a steaming brook." },
      orfeo:   { passages: [4], note: "A great rock with a vertical cleft, three miles through solid stone, onto the bright country." },
      owain: { passages: [2, 3], note: "The fountain under the great tree, with its slab and chained silver bowl: pour the water and the marvel comes. The apparatus is named openly, exactly as Pwyll\u2019s Gorsedd custom is \u2014 do this at this marked place, and the Otherworld answers." },
      branwen: false,
      manawydan: { passages: [2, 6], note: "The very same Gorsedd of Arberth as Pwyll's, two generations on: it is on the mound that the four sit when the thunder and mist fall and the land empties, and on the mound that Manawydan later builds the gallows that breaks the spell. The marked place where the Otherworld answers — used to curse the land and, at the last, to lift the curse." },
      gloss: "Pwyll's Gorsedd Arberth is the canonical Welsh form — a grass-covered mound above the court where the apparatus is openly named (sit here and a marvel comes). Gawain's Green Chapel is the same shape (grass-grown barrow with openings) restaged as Pearl-Poet wilderness. Orfeo's rock-cleft is the most decisively spatial. Only Culhwch refuses the motif — its Otherworld is the geometry of unreachability, not a marked place. Owain joins them — the fountain is its marked threshold, named as openly as Pwyll’s Gorsedd. Five of the eight tales need such a summoning-door; Culhwch and Branwen do not — Branwen’s door, the forbidden one at Gwales, is a tabu to be left shut, not a threshold to be used (see C611 below). Manawydan reuses Pwyll’s very mound, the one place in the corpus that serves twice — to lay the enchantment and to lift it." },

    { code: "K1810", name: "Deception by disguise",
      culhwch: { passages: [11], note: "Cei as sword-burnisher to enter Wrnach's hall — the giant's death by his own blade." },
      pwyll:   { passages: [1, 4], note: "Two registers of disguise. Pwyll wears Arawn's body for a year while Arawn wears his — by mutual consent, not deception of the other. Then Pwyll dresses as a beggar at Gwawl's feast to spring the bag-trick — the trick that recovers Rhiannon." },
      gawain:  { passages: [1, 2, 3, 4], note: "Three masks: Bertilak is the Green Knight, the ancient lady is Morgan, the lady acts at Bertilak's direction. The poem keeps the audience inside Gawain's ignorance for two whole Fitts." },
      orfeo:   { passages: [4, 5, 6], note: "Orfeo as minstrel at the Fairy King's gate, as harper-from-heathenness to the steward, in borrowed beggar's clothes at Winchester." },
      owain: { passages: [4, 5, 6, 8], note: "Pervasive: Luned\u2019s ring of invisibility; her pretended embassy to Arthur\u2019s court; the disguised three-day duel (Gwalchmei in a borrowed robe, neither cousin knowing the other); Owain fighting \u201cin his own stead\u201d for Luned at the stake." },
      branwen: false,
      manawydan: { passages: [6], note: "The enchanter Llwyd works the climax entirely in disguise, approaching the gallows three times in rising rank — poor scholar, mounted priest, bishop with a baggage-train — each pressing Manawydan to free the mouse. Antagonist-side disguise (like Bertilak's), tripled into a folktale escalation." },
      math: { passages: [1, 4], note: "Gwydion's constant method: he enters Pryderi's court as the chief of a company of bards (and again at Caer Aranrhod), and plays a gilded shoemaker at Aranrhod's gate to trick a name onto Lleu. Disguise as the trickster's working tool — and, like Pwyll's beggar, on the protagonist's own side." },
      vitamerlini: { passages: [4], note: "Ganieda shows one boy three times, disguised (new clothes and cut hair, then a girl's dress), to make Merlin's threefold-death prophecy seem a madman's contradiction." },
      gloss: "Seven of the eight tales use the motif, in markedly different moral vectors (Owain is the most saturated of all: the ring of invisibility, the pretended embassy, the disguised duel, the fight “in his own stead”). Culhwch and Gawain use disguise on the antagonist's side (Cei to enter the giant's hall; Bertilak to obscure himself); Pwyll and Orfeo use it on the hero's side (Pwyll to recover Rhiannon, Orfeo to recover Heurodis). Pwyll uniquely uses it consensually first (the year-exchange with Arawn) before using it adversarially second (the beggar at Gwawl's feast). Branwen is the exception: its deception is concealment (warriors hidden as meal-bags) and treachery (the false peace), not disguise of identity." },

    { code: "N777", name: "Adventure follows the hunt",
      culhwch: false,
      pwyll:   { passages: [1], note: "The opening of the whole tale: Pwyll's hunt at Glyn Cuch summons Arawn's hunt, the year-exchange and the rest of the story. The canonical British wonder-tale opening — older than its Middle English re-uses." },
      gawain:  { passages: [3], note: "Three days of paralleled hunts cross-cut with three bedroom encounters; the hunt outside structurally summons and pays for the test inside." },
      orfeo:   { passages: [3, 4], note: "The sixty hawking ladies are an Otherworld hunt; Orfeo follows them through the rock-cleft. The hunt-as-threshold preserved cleanly." },
      owain: { passages: [8], note: "Echo only: the hospitable earl\u2019s two sons are seized by the giant while hunting on the mountain. Owain\u2019s own quest is summoned by a tale told at court, not by a hunt." },
      branwen: false,
      manawydan: { passages: [4], note: "The canonical shape again, and the disaster of the branch: a morning's hunt flushes a shining-white boar that will not run like quarry but leads Pryderi and Manawydan to the caer that was never there \u2014 and into the trap that takes Pryderi and Rhiannon. The Otherworld lure straight out of Pwyll's tradition." },
      math: { passages: [5], note: "The hunt brings the betrayal: a stag-chase lodges Gronw Pebr overnight at Lleu's court while Lleu is away, and from that first look he and Blodeuwedd plot Lleu's death. The hunt-at-the-threshold turned into the engine of adultery and murder." },
      gloss: "The hunt as plot-engine in five of the eight — and Pwyll the locus classicus (Owain keeps only an echo, the earl’s sons taken at the hunt). The Middle English poems inherit the form from the older Welsh wonder-tale tradition: a hunt at a wood-border summons the Otherworld. Culhwch's great boar-hunt is the structural exception — there it is the climax of the quest, not its conjurer." },

    { code: "F771.6", name: "Castle in the wilderness / of crystal",
      culhwch: false,
      pwyll:   false,
      gawain:  { passages: [2], note: "Hautdesert appears in the trees in answer to Gawain's prayer to Mary on Christmas Eve — \"a castle full comely, gleamed and shone.\"" },
      orfeo:   { passages: [4], note: "The crystal castle of the Otherworld: outer wall of clear crystal, a hundred towers, red-gold buttresses, precious-stone chambers, the worst pillar of burnished gold." },
      owain: { passages: [2, 3], note: "The \u201cgreat shining castle\u201d (kaer fawr lywychedig) Cynon and Owain reach across the plain, and the towered castle of the hospitable earl \u2014 resplendent, but rationalised as real fortresses, closer to Gawain\u2019s Hautdesert than to Orfeo\u2019s crystal." },
      branwen: false,
      manawydan: { passages: [4], note: "The enchanted caer — “a great, lofty fort with new-built work upon it,” standing where the four had never seen so much as a stone — is the Welsh tradition's wonder-castle as pure illusion: it appears for the hunt and vanishes in thunder and mist with its captives inside. Closer to Orfeo's fairy-architecture than to Gawain's rationalised keep, but a trap, not a court." },
      gloss: "A wonder-castle the two English poems share — and which Owain shows the Welsh tradition can also raise. Both English poems produce a wonder-castle out of the wilderness; Gawain's is rationalised as a great medieval fortress, Orfeo's is unembarrassedly fairy-architecture. The Welsh tales both stage their Otherworld as an inhabited hall (in Pwyll) or as offstage geometry (in Culhwch) — never as a wonder-architecture visible from the outside. Owain’s “great shining castle” rising across the plain is a third, rationalised like Gawain’s rather than crystal like Orfeo’s. Three registers of the same astonishment; Branwen raises a built house too, but as a death-trap (the iron house, the meal-bag hall), not a wonder." },

    { code: "F375", name: "Mortal returns from the Otherworld",
      culhwch: false,
      pwyll:   { passages: [2], note: "Pwyll returns from his year in Annwn unmarked and welcomed — Arawn's people praised the year's rule and Pwyll's own people received him as if no exchange had happened. The cleanest return arc in the corpus: no scar, no sash, no aged face." },
      gawain:  { passages: [4], note: "Gawain returns marked — nick on the neck, the green sash bound under his left arm — a partial return." },
      orfeo:   { passages: [5, 6], note: "Heurodis returns unchanged; Orfeo returns altered only by ten years of mourning that the bath and shaving undo. A full return." },
      owain: { passages: [6, 9], note: "Owain returns twice \u2014 from the fountain-realm to Arthur\u2019s court with the company (VI), and from the madness-wilderness, healed, at the tale\u2019s end (IX). Each is a re-entry from a place outside ordinary life." },
      branwen: { passages: [6], note: "The seven survivors return from the timeless feast at Gwales bearing Br\u00e2n\u2019s head \u2014 the bleakest return in the corpus: Branwen dies of grief on the way (on the Alaw), Caswallon has usurped Britain in their absence, and the head is buried at the White Hill. A return that restores no order." },
      manawydan: { passages: [6], note: "Pryderi and Rhiannon return from the vanished caer where they stood held fast and dumb — released unharmed when Manawydan wins the bargain, and the wasted land restored with them. The cleanest recovery in the corpus after Pwyll's: the cost was borne not by the taken but by the patience of the one who stayed." },
      vitamerlini: { passages: [9, 10], note: "Inverted: Arthur is borne <em>to</em> the Otherworld isle and does not return — laid in Morgen's care to be healed 'if he stays a long time.' The once-and-future king: the return deferred, not made." },
      gloss: "Six returns, six costs. Gawain comes back changed; Orfeo and Heurodis come back themselves; Pwyll comes back better — he gains an alliance and a name (Pen Annwn). The Welsh tale frames the Otherworld as a place a king may simply rule for a year and step out of; the English poems frame it as a place whose visit is paid for, either in the body or in years. Branwen’s is the bleakest: the seven come back from a feast out of time to a usurped Britain, and Branwen herself dies on the road." },

    { code: "H1010", name: "Impossible tasks",
      culhwch: { passages: [8], note: "The ~40 anoethau Ysbaddaden imposes on pain of death — clear and reap a hill in a day, fetch the comb between the boar's ears, win the cauldron from Ireland." },
      pwyll:   false,
      gawain:  false,
      orfeo:   false,
      owain: false,
      branwen: false,
      gloss: "The signature motif of Culhwch and absent from the other five. The wonder-tale's task-quest belongs to the oldest Welsh stratum; Pwyll uses a bargain and a trick where Culhwch would use a list of labours; the English romances substitute tests of honour and rash bargains for impossible labours. Culhwch alone keeps the catalogue." },

    { code: "G530.2", name: "Help from the ogre's daughter",
      culhwch: { passages: [6], note: "Olwen coaches Culhwch on how to out-promise her giant father — the precise motif at its purest." },
      pwyll:   { passages: [4], note: "The same shape, refigured: Rhiannon (whose father Hyfaidd Hen has given her to Gwawl against her will) coaches Pwyll on how to out-promise the rival suitor with the bag-trick. The bride-helps-suitor-against-father pattern, with the suitor's rival in the father's structural slot." },
      gawain:  false,
      orfeo:   false,
      owain: { passages: [4, 5], note: "The same helper-woman pattern displaced from bride to maid: Luned (not the widow herself) coaches and contrives the match, talking the grieving Countess into wedding her husband\u2019s killer. The clever woman who enables the marriage \u2014 Luned beside Olwen and Rhiannon." },
      branwen: false,
      gloss: "A motif the Welsh romances share against the English pair. Olwen, Rhiannon and Owain’s Luned all bring the hero past the figure barring the marriage — Olwen against her giant father, Rhiannon against her father’s chosen suitor, Luned against her grieving mistress’s refusal. All three are woman-led recoveries; the English poems have queens taken or tested but never won by a helper’s wit; and Branwen does not share it — its marriage is arranged between the brothers and undone by one of them, not won by a bride’s helper." },

    // ── Single-tale, or shared by only two ─────────────────────────
    { code: "E783", name: "The vital (talking) severed head",
      culhwch: false,
      pwyll:   false,
      gawain:  { passages: [1], note: "The Green Knight's head, held in his hand from horseback, turns its eyes on Camelot and speaks the rules of the return-match." },
      orfeo:   false,
      owain: false,
      branwen: { passages: [6], note: "<em>Urddawl Ben</em>, the Noble Head: mortally wounded by a poisoned spear, Br\u00e2n has his own head struck off; it stays undecayed, eats, talks and counsels the seven survivors through seven years at Harlech and fourscore at Gwales, and is buried at the White Hill of London facing France as a talisman against invasion. The canonical Insular instance of the vital severed head." },
      gloss: "The corpus’s headline cross-tale link, Thompson E783 (“vital head”). Branwen’s Brân is the canonical Insular instance — his struck-off head stays undecayed, feasting and counselling the seven for fourscore years before its burial at the White Hill — and Gawain’s Green Knight, who lifts his own severed head from the floor to speak, is its great later literary cousin. The Second Branch and the Pearl-Poet’s romance, three centuries apart, share the living head: exactly the resonance this grid exists to surface." },

    { code: "F379.1", name: "The half-taken — body remains as if dead, self in fairyland",
      culhwch: false,
      pwyll:   false,
      gawain:  false,
      orfeo:   { passages: [4], note: "The yard inside the Otherworld castle: figures held in the postures they were taken in — some headless, some bound and mad, women in childbed, sleeping at noon. <em>Thought dede and nare nought.</em>" },
      owain: false,
      branwen: false,
      manawydan: { passages: [4], note: "The corpus's closest cousin to Orfeo's half-taken: Pryderi, and then Rhiannon, grip the golden bowl and are held fast — hands stuck to the bowl, feet to the slab, speech taken — frozen living in the caer and carried off with it when it vanishes. Held between worlds, neither dead nor free, exactly as Orfeo's stilled figures are." },
      gloss: "Orfeo's most distinctive contribution to the Otherworld tradition — and Manawydan its one true cousin in the corpus. The Third Branch's golden-bowl captives (held fast, speechless, taken with the vanishing caer) work the same uncanny logic as Orfeo's yard of the half-taken; neither Culhwch nor Gawain nor Pwyll has anything quite like it. One of the most uncanny figures in the material, and one Thompson's index does not fully cover." },

    { code: "Z356", name: "The unique exception (named within a catalogue)",
      culhwch: false,
      pwyll:   false,
      gawain:  { passages: [2], note: "The pentangle — five points each twined into the next — named explicitly <em>the endeles knot</em> within the catalogue of arming." },
      orfeo:   { passages: [4], note: "<em>Al that lond was ever light</em> — the ever-light Otherworld, named separately from the catalogue of the castle's wonders." },
      owain: false,
      branwen: false,
      gloss: "Both English poems use the same rhetorical device: stop a catalogue of wonders to mark one wonder as unique among them. The Pearl-Poet does it with the pentangle, the Orfeo poet with the ever-light. The Welsh tales prefer to name things in lists or not name them at all — no such marked exception in either Culhwch or Pwyll." },

    // ── Brought into the corpus by Pwyll ───────────────────────────
    { code: "D1626.1", name: "Magic horse that cannot be overtaken",
      culhwch: false,
      pwyll:   { passages: [3], note: "Rhiannon's pale-white horse: walks at an easy pace, and yet no runner, no horseman, no rider however fast comes anywhere near catching her. Three days of attempts; only Pwyll's spoken asking halts her." },
      gawain:  false,
      orfeo:   { passages: [3], note: "Echo: the snow-white horses of the Fairy King's retinue and the sixty hawking ladies — never lamed, never caught, always at the threshold." },
      owain: false,
      branwen: false,
      gloss: "Pwyll is the canonical Insular instance: Rhiannon's horse is a recoverable god (the horse-goddess Epona, demoted; <em>Rigantona</em>'s mount). Orfeo's snow-white fairy horses preserve the figure in attenuated form three centuries later. The Welsh tale anchors a motif the English lay inherits." },

    { code: "K1601", name: "Magic container that holds more than it should (badger-in-the-bag)",
      culhwch: false,
      pwyll:   { passages: [4], note: "Rhiannon's never-filling bag. Gwawl is invited to press the food down with his own two feet; Pwyll knots the bag shut over his head and blows the horn; a hundred horsemen come running. The trick that recovers the queen, naming the children's game <em>byw'r mochyn yn y cwd</em> — 'play badger-in-the-bag'." },
      gawain:  false,
      orfeo:   false,
      owain: false,
      branwen: false,
      manawydan: { passages: [6], note: "The trick comes due. Llwyd son of Cil Coed lays the entire wasteland-enchantment of Dyfed — the mist, the empty land, the caer, the mice — to avenge Gwawl son of Clud for this very humiliation, visited a generation late on Pwyll's son Pryderi and Pwyll's widow Rhiannon. The First Branch's lever of recovery becomes the Third Branch's cause of ruin." },
      gloss: "A signature Welsh trick-motif — and the corpus's single deepest inter-tale link. Pwyll uses an enchanted container as the lever of recovery (and gives Wales a children's game in the doing); Manawydan, two Branches and a generation on, is the long payback for that same trick — Llwyd enchants all of Dyfed to avenge the bagged Gwawl. The English poems do not reproduce the magic-bag motif; their tricks are bargains and disguises, not enchanted objects; Branwen’s leather meal-bags (armed men passed off as flour) are a mundane cousin — concealment, not enchantment (see K754.1)." },

    { code: "P528", name: "The calumniated wife (ATU 707)",
      culhwch: false,
      pwyll:   { passages: [5], note: "Rhiannon's penance. The six women, terrified of being punished for losing the prince's son, smear blood on the sleeping queen and accuse her of killing him. Pwyll refuses to set her aside; she sits at the gate for seven years, telling her story and offering to carry visitors on her back. The wife wrongfully accused of infanticide — a structural backbone of the ATU 707 tale-type." },
      gawain:  false,
      orfeo:   false,
      owain: false,
      branwen: false,
      gloss: "The classic calumniated-wife motif, and Pwyll among its earliest Insular witnesses. The penance is handled with structural gravity — Pwyll keeps her even when his nobles press for her dismissal, and the false accusation is dissolved by Teirnon's evidence rather than her self-defence. Neither the English pair nor Culhwch puts an accused queen on stage; the Mabinogi does it twice — Rhiannon here in the First Branch and Branwen, persecuted, in the Second (see S411 below) — and Owain echoes it with the condemned maid Luned (see the archetype grid)." },

    { code: "B538.1", name: "Severed monster's arm at the window",
      culhwch: false,
      pwyll:   { passages: [6], note: "Teirnon's vigil: at midnight the mare gives birth, a great dark clawed arm reaches through the high window for the foal, and Teirnon strikes the arm off at the elbow. From outside there comes a scream; the foal stays. The unseen power is never shown — only its severed limb." },
      gawain:  false,
      orfeo:   false,
      owain: false,
      branwen: false,
      gloss: "A motif with deep North-Sea resonance — the closest cousin is Beowulf's tearing of Grendel's arm at Heorot. Pwyll's branch is the Insular Welsh witness of the figure. Outside our five-tale corpus the parallel is the most striking thing about Pwyll's Movement V–VI." },

    { code: "T563", name: "Recognition of unknown son by resemblance",
      culhwch: false,
      pwyll:   { passages: [6], note: "Teirnon, having been Pwyll's man years before, looks at the boy he raised and sees Pwyll's face. The boy is brought to Arberth; everyone in the hall agrees on the likeness; Rhiannon is released from her penance. Recognition not by ring or token but by the printed face." },
      gawain:  false,
      orfeo:   false,
      owain: false,
      branwen: false,
      gloss: "Pwyll's recognition arc is built on the simplest possible token — the resemblance itself. Orfeo's recognition by the harp's tune and Gawain's by the green sash work the same structural slot through objects; only Pwyll lets the body do it. Culhwch never returns to be recognised." },

    { code: "F302", name: "Fairy bride / mortal weds Otherworld woman",
      culhwch: false,
      pwyll:   { passages: [3], note: "Rhiannon comes openly from the Otherworld on her pale-white horse to choose Pwyll. She is the canonical fairy bride of the Insular tradition — Epona / Rigantona in human form, choosing a Welsh prince over a fairy suitor (Gwawl)." },
      gawain:  { passages: [2, 3], note: "Echo, partial: Lady Bertilak is mortal in the surface story but bound to Morgan's Otherworld household at Hautdesert; she courts Gawain at her host's bidding." },
      orfeo:   false,
      owain: { passages: [4, 5], note: "The Countess of the Fountain \u2014 lady of the Otherworld-touched storm-spring, won by the knight who kills her defender. Less overtly fae than Rhiannon, but the bride of a marvel-domain, like Lady Bertilak bent toward the mortal end of the scale." },
      branwen: false,
      manawydan: { passages: [1], note: "The same fairy bride, a second time: Rhiannon — Pwyll's Otherworld queen — is given in marriage again, now to Manawydan, and again the match is made by talk and consent rather than capture. The fairy queen re-wed, the dynastic thread of the First Branch carried into the Third." },
      math: { passages: [5], note: "The motif turned inside out: Math and Gwydion do not win an Otherworld bride but make one — Blodeuwedd, conjured from oak, broom and meadowsweet to beat Aranrhod's curse that Lleu have no wife of any earthly race. A bride of no race at all, made to order and owing no loyalty she was not given (see the made-wife row below)." },
      gloss: "Pwyll's Rhiannon is the locus classicus — a fairy queen who chooses to enter the mortal world and marry within it (and, in the Third Branch, marries again, to Manawydan). The Hautdesert lady is the same shape bent: a court woman in an Otherworld house, sent to test rather than to choose. Olwen and Heurodis are mortal; the role belongs to the Welsh-Insular figures: Rhiannon directly, and in shadow both Lady Bertilak and Owain’s Countess of the Fountain, ladies of a marvel-house bent toward the mortal end of the scale." },

    // ── Brought into the corpus by Owain ─────────────────
    { code: "B301", name: "Grateful animal helper (the lion)",
      culhwch: false, pwyll: false, gawain: false, orfeo: false,
      owain: { passages: [8, 9], note: "Owain frees a lion from a serpent, and the beast follows him \u201clike a greyhound he had reared\u201d \u2014 fetching food, keeping watch, breaking through walls to fight at his side against the giant and the two pages. The grateful-animal helper (ATU 156, the Androcles stock); it names Chr\u00e9tien\u2019s twin, le Chevalier au Lion." },
      branwen: false,
      gloss: "Owain\u2019s signature contribution, unique in the corpus: a helper bound to the hero by gratitude rather than kinship (Culhwch\u2019s band), magic (Gawain\u2019s girdle), or instrument (Orfeo\u2019s harp). The lion is loyalty made flesh \u2014 and the moral mirror of the faith Owain himself breaks." },

    { code: "D2143.1", name: "Storm raised by magic (the fountain-rite)",
      culhwch: false, pwyll: false, gawain: false, orfeo: false,
      owain: { passages: [2, 3, 6], note: "Pour a bowlful of the fountain\u2019s water on the slab and a tempest of thunder and hail strips the wood bare; then the Black Knight rides to answer. A weather-rite bound to a place \u2014 the engine of the whole romance, raised by Cynon, Owain, and Cei in turn." },
      branwen: false,
      gloss: "A motif none of the four native tales carries: a controllable, place-bound storm that summons a guardian. Its closest cousin is Chr\u00e9tien\u2019s fountain of Barenton in Broc\u00e9liande \u2014 the Welsh\u2194Continental kinship showing at the level of the single motif, not just the plot." },

    { code: "D1361.17", name: "Ring of invisibility",
      culhwch: false, pwyll: false, gawain: false, orfeo: false,
      owain: { passages: [4, 7], note: "Luned\u2019s ring: turn the stone into the palm and close the hand, and \u201cas long as you hide it, it will hide you.\u201d It carries the trapped Owain out of the portcullis-cage, past the household come to kill him; in Movement VII it is stripped from his finger, the public sign of his broken word." },
      branwen: false,
      gloss: "The corpus\u2019s only true invisibility token. Pwyll\u2019s disguises are bodily (Arawn\u2019s form) and Orfeo\u2019s sartorial (the beggar\u2019s rags); only Owain has the object that simply unsees its wearer." },

    { code: "D1244", name: "Magic ointment / healing balsam",
      culhwch: false, pwyll: false, gawain: false, orfeo: false,
      owain: { passages: [7], note: "The widowed Countess of the park\u2019s precious balsam, poured over the mad Owain\u2019s heart (and, by her kind maid, over all of him), which raises him from his wasted state and heals him \u201cfairer than before.\u201d The tale\u2019s instrument of grace \u2014 medicinal, not fae." },
      branwen: false,
      gloss: "Owain\u2019s recovery turns on a medicinal wonder rather than an Otherworld one: where Orfeo is recovered out of Faerie itself and Pwyll restored simply by stepping back into his own body, Owain is healed by a noblewoman\u2019s salve. Grace made physical." },

    { code: "F567", name: "The wild man of the woods (madness)",
      culhwch: false, pwyll: false, gawain: false, orfeo: false,
      owain: { passages: [7], note: "His word broken and his ring stripped, Owain runs mad and naked into the wastes \u2014 clothes rotting, hair growing over him \u2014 and lives among the deer until even they leave him. The native Brittonic gwyllt, the wild man whose reason is lost to guilt." },
      branwen: false,
      vitamerlini: { passages: [1, 2], note: "Merlin <em>is</em> the wild man — <em>fit silvester homo</em>, the locus classicus of the motif; cf. Owain's madness among the deer (Owain, Mvt VIII)." },
      gloss: "The corpus\u2019s only descent into madness, and a deeply Welsh one: the gwyllt behind Myrddin Wyllt (Merlin) and the Irish Suibhne. The tale with a French twin reaches, for its nadir, into the oldest native stratum of all \u2014 reason lost in the wilderness and won back there." },

    { code: "K811", name: "Murderous host / the treacherous welcome-feast",
      culhwch: false, pwyll: false, gawain: false, orfeo: false,
      owain: { passages: [9], note: "The Black Oppressor (y Du Traws): guests received \u201cwith joy and honour,\u201d made drunk, then slaughtered for their goods, their corpses heaped in the hall, their twenty-four widows kept in rags. Owain subdues him and turns the house of spoil into a hospice." },
      branwen: { passages: [2], note: "The cauldron\u2019s back-story: the Irish pack the giant Llasar and his wife into an iron house and heat it white-hot to kill them \u2014 victims lured into a house and burned (the couple burst out through the glowing wall). The lured-and-burned house, Insular and grim, shared with Owain\u2019s murderous host." },
      vitamerlini: { passages: [11], note: "The Night of the Long Knives — Hengist's Saxons cut down the British nobles at a peace-feast — recounted in Merlin's chronicle of the Saxon wars." },
      gloss: "The dark inversion of the corpus’s gracious hosts, in its two grimmest tales. Owain stages the treacherous welcome-feast (the Black Oppressor, who drowns his guests in drink and slaughters them — and is uniquely spared and converted into a hospitaller); Branwen stages the lured-and-burned house (the iron house heated white-hot on the giant couple, and the meal-bag hall raised to honour Brân). Welcome turned death-trap, shared across the Welsh romance and the Second Branch." },
    // ── Brought into the corpus by Branwen ─────────────────
    { code: "D1171.3", name: "The Cauldron of Rebirth (magic cauldron)",
      culhwch: false, pwyll: false, owain: false, orfeo: false, gawain: false,
      branwen: { passages: [2, 5], note: "<em>Pair Dadeni</em>, the Cauldron of Rebirth, brought from a lake in Ireland (with its back-story of the unkillable giant-couple and the iron house): cast a slain man in and by dawn he rises as good a fighter as before. Brân gives it to Matholwch as amends for Efnisien’s outrage; it returns in the war as the engine of his host’s ruin. The branch’s central magical object." },
      gloss: "Branwen’s signature object, and a deep one: the regenerative cauldron belongs to the wider Insular tradition — the cauldron of Diwrnach won in Culhwch, the cauldron of the Head of Annwn in <em>Preiddeu Annwn</em> — and Loomis and others traced the line forward to the Grail itself. The corpus carries the cauldron-of-plenty motif only here; the Mabinogi’s contribution to the legend’s central mutating symbol." },

    { code: "E64.1", name: "Resurrection by cauldron — the dead return, but dumb",
      culhwch: false, pwyll: false, owain: false, orfeo: false, gawain: false,
      branwen: { passages: [2, 5], note: "The cauldron’s terrible condition: the slain rise whole and strong, but mute — never able to speak again. In Ireland the Irish cast their dead in each night and the men of Britain cannot win, until Efnisien feigns death, is thrown in alive, and bursts the cauldron (and his own heart). Resurrection without the soul’s voice." },
      gloss: "The corpus’s only resurrection motif — and its bleakest marvel. Where the other tales recover the lost from the Otherworld whole (Heurodis, Pryderi, the healed Owain), Branwen alone returns the dead to battle stripped of speech, a regeneration that is its own kind of death." },

    { code: "C611", name: "The forbidden door (the door at Gwales)",
      culhwch: false, pwyll: false, owain: false, orfeo: false, gawain: false,
      branwen: { passages: [6], note: "At Gwales the seven survivors feast fourscore years out of time, all grief forgotten and Brân’s living head their guest, while two doors stand open and the third — toward Aber Henfelen and Cornwall — must not be opened. Heilyn opens it; memory and loss flood back in an instant and the timeless idyll ends. Thompson C611, the forbidden chamber, in its noblest Insular form." },
      manawydan: { passages: [4], note: "The structural inverse, in the very next branch: Manawydan forbids Pryderi to enter the enchanted caer (“whoever laid the enchantment caused this fort to be here”), and Pryderi's crossing of that forbidden threshold begins his captivity. Branwen's tabu must be left shut; Manawydan's must not be crossed — the same interdiction-and-violation logic, mirrored." },
      gloss: "Branwen's is the noblest Insular form — the forbidden door whose opening ends an enchantment — and Manawydan, the next branch, mirrors it: an interdiction against entering the caer whose breach begins one. Between them the Mabinogi stages the threshold-tabu both ways (the door that must stay shut, the fort that must not be entered), where the other tales make the marked place a threshold to be used (contrast the Gorsedd, the Green Chapel, the rock-cleft and the fountain at F156)." },

    { code: "K754.1", name: "Warriors concealed in bags (the flour-bag ambush)",
      culhwch: false, pwyll: false, owain: false, orfeo: false, gawain: false,
      branwen: { passages: [4], note: "The Irish hang two hundred leather bags on the pillars of the house built for Brân, an armed man in each, and tell anyone who asks that they hold meal. Efnisien, reading the trap, goes down the row crushing each hidden head through the bone — “What is in this bag?” “Meal” — and caps it with a grim englyn. The hidden-army ambush undone by counter-deception." },
      gloss: "A close cousin of the lured-and-burned house (K811): where the iron house kills by fire, the meal-bag hall kills by concealed men. Branwen pairs the two as the same Insular nightmare of the treacherous dwelling — and gives the counter-stroke to the very strife-maker who began the ruin." },

    { code: "S302", name: "Murder of a child (cast into the fire)",
      culhwch: false, pwyll: false, owain: false, orfeo: false, gawain: false,
      branwen: { passages: [5], note: "At the feast of reconciliation, with the kingship conferred on the boy Gwern, Efnisien is called to fondle his nephew — and flings the child headlong into the fire. Branwen would leap in after him but Brân holds her back; the hall erupts into the war that empties both islands. The killing of the innocent child-king, told with stark, unbearable brevity." },
      gloss: "The corpus’s single act of child-murder, and the spark of its catastrophe. Where the other tales harm children only by theft-and-recovery (Pryderi, the earl’s sons in Owain) and give them back, Branwen alone lets the child die — the alliance, embodied in Gwern, murdered with him." },

    { code: "S411", name: "The persecuted / banished wife (Branwen's blow)",
      culhwch: false, pwyll: false, owain: false, orfeo: false, gawain: false,
      branwen: { passages: [3], note: "Not calumny (Pwyll’s Rhiannon) but scapegoating: to avenge Efnisien’s insult on someone, Matholwch’s court drives Branwen from the king’s bed to the kitchen, where the butcher boxes her ear every day for three years. The blow — <em>paluawt Branwen</em> — is named in the colophon as one of the Three Unhappy Blows of Britain." },
      gloss: "The Second Branch’s suffering queen, sister-figure to the First Branch’s calumniated wife (Pwyll’s Rhiannon, P528) and to Owain’s condemned maid (Luned). The Mabinogi stages the wronged woman again and again; here she is punished not for a crime she is accused of but simply as the nearest target of a grudge." },

    // ── Brought into the corpus by Manawydan ─────────────────
    { code: "D2090", name: "Land laid waste by enchantment (the wasteland)",
      culhwch: false, pwyll: false, branwen: false, owain: false, orfeo: false, gawain: false,
      manawydan: { passages: [2, 5], note: "Thunder and a fall of mist on the Gorsedd of Arberth empty the seven cantrefs of Dyfed — no house, no beast, no smoke, no neighbour — and the crops that do grow are reaped by night. The whole branch is the labour of lifting it." },
      gloss: "The corpus's one true wasteland, and its only fully-undone one: the Insular cousin of the Continental Grail terre gaste — a kingdom sunk into desolation by a magical act and waiting to be redeemed. Where Branwen empties two islands by war and leaves them empty, Manawydan empties one by enchantment and makes it whole again — the bright mirror of its prequel's ruin." },

    { code: "D2171", name: "Magic adhesion — the golden-bowl trap",
      culhwch: false, pwyll: false, branwen: false, owain: false, orfeo: false, gawain: false,
      manawydan: { passages: [4], note: "Within the vanishing caer, a golden bowl rests on a marble slab, hung from four chains that rise into the air with no visible end. Pryderi grips it and his hands stick fast, his feet to the slab, his speech gone; Rhiannon, following, is caught the same way. A snare baited with gold." },
      gloss: "The corpus's sticky-trap, kin to the wide tar-baby family (Thompson D2171) but turned into a beautiful Otherworld lure: the captive is not killed or carried but fixed in place and silenced. Paired with the false-donor logic of the bowl, it is Manawydan's distinctive contribution to the Otherworld-trap repertoire." },

    { code: "D117", name: "Transformation of people into animals",
      culhwch: false, pwyll: false, branwen: false, owain: false, orfeo: false, gawain: false,
      manawydan: { passages: [5, 6], note: "Llwyd shape-shifts his whole household — and on the third night his pregnant wife and the ladies of his court — into the innumerable host of mice that strips Manawydan's wheat ear by ear. A war-band of revenge delivered as vermin; the one mouse too heavy to flee is the wife, and the hinge of the whole resolution." },
      math: { passages: [2, 5, 6], note: "The transformation-branch proper: Math's wand turns Gwydion and Gilfaethwy into three successive pairs of wild beasts (deer, boar, wolves) as punishment, Lleu into a wounded eagle, and Blodeuwedd into an owl. Where Manawydan's is a single mass shape-shift, Math's is the corpus's sustained vocabulary of metamorphosis." },
      gloss: "Turning people into animals is the shared magic of the two enchanter-branches and nowhere else in the corpus. Manawydan does it once and en masse — an army and a court reduced to mice; Math does it again and again, as punishment (the brothers as beasts), as near-death (Lleu the eagle) and as sentence (Blodeuwedd the owl). The Mabinogi's metamorphosis-vocabulary, worked in both by the same instrument — the wand (see below)." },

    { code: "Q281", name: "Mercy — the villain spared, revenge renounced",
      culhwch: false, pwyll: false, branwen: false, owain: false, orfeo: false, gawain: false,
      manawydan: { passages: [6], note: "Holding the enchanter's pregnant wife on the gallows and every card in the game, Manawydan asks not for vengeance but for guarantees — Pryderi and Rhiannon freed, the spell lifted from Dyfed for ever, and a sworn promise of no future revenge on anyone — and then spares Llwyd. Mercy written as the last clause of the contract." },
      gloss: "The deliberate counter-move to the corpus's appetite for punishment (Culhwch's beheading of Ysbaddaden, Owain's killings, Branwen's mutual ruin): Manawydan refuses to punish, and uses his total advantage to end the revenge-cycle Pwyll began rather than extend it. It rhymes with Pwyll's own release of the bagged Gwawl on a sworn no-vengeance — the same family choosing, twice, to stop. Math is the counter-case: it punishes everyone, twice over and exactly (the beast-sentence, the owl, the return-blow)." },

    // ── Brought into the corpus by Math (and shared with Manawydan) ─────────────────
    { code: "D1254.1", name: "The magic wand (hudlath)",
      culhwch: false, pwyll: false, branwen: false, owain: false, orfeo: false, gawain: false,
      manawydan: { passages: [6], note: "Llwyd strikes the captured mouse with a <em>hudlath</em> and restores her to a woman — the disenchanting wand that, with the bargain, lifts the wasteland of the Third Branch." },
      math: { passages: [2, 3, 6], note: "The branch's central instrument: Math's (and Gwydion's) <em>hudlath</em> tests Aranrhod, turns the brothers to beasts and back, and calls the wounded eagle down into a man. One object that transforms, punishes and heals alike." },
      gloss: "The wand is the shared signature of the Mabinogi's two enchanter-branches — Math and Manawydan — and of nowhere else in the corpus. In Math it does the work of the whole tale; in Manawydan it works the final restoration. The same magical vocabulary (and the same word, <em>hudlath</em>) reaching across the Third and Fourth Branches." },

    { code: "T543", name: "Woman created from flowers (the made wife)",
      culhwch: false, pwyll: false, branwen: false, manawydan: false, owain: false, orfeo: false, gawain: false,
      math: { passages: [5], note: "Blodeuwedd — \"Flower-Face\" — conjured by Math and Gwydion from the blossoms of oak, broom and meadowsweet to beat Aranrhod's curse that Lleu have no wife of any earthly race. The artificial wife, made for one man and owing no loyalty she was not given; she loves another at first sight, and her betrayal is the proof that a thing made against nature carries its own undoing." },
      gloss: "The corpus's one wholly made being — a wife manufactured, not born or won. Where Pwyll's Rhiannon enters the world as a fairy bride and Owain's Countess is won by combat, Math's hero is given a woman with no kin, no human nature, no given loyalty. One of the most resonant inventions in Welsh myth, and the most alive in the after-tradition — Saunders Lewis's verse-play, Alan Garner's <em>The Owl Service</em>, and beyond." },

    { code: "Z312", name: "The 'neither–nor' fatal condition",
      culhwch: false, pwyll: false, branwen: false, manawydan: false, owain: false, orfeo: false, gawain: false,
      math: { passages: [5], note: "Lleu can be killed only under impossible, liminal conditions — not in a house nor out, not on horse nor foot, by a spear a year in the making and worked only at the forbidden hour of Sunday mass, with one foot on a cauldron-rim and one on a buck. The treacherous wife coaxes the riddle out of him and betrays it; the murder is staged to match it exactly, and even so he escapes as an eagle." },
      gloss: "The hero invulnerable except at the threshold of every category — a deep Indo-European pattern, the hedged death of a god. Math is the corpus's instance, and it carries the international structure of the secret-weakness tale (the ATU 590-cluster): the wife who learns, by a false show of love, the one near-impossible way her husband can be killed, and hands it to her lover." },
  ],

  proppIntro: "The 31 Propp functions laid against the nine poems. <em>✓</em> marks present; <em>·</em> marks the function as sharply absent (named in our story graphs as a meaningful refusal). The dense top — the wonder-tale's quest spine — is present in all eight of the original poems; the ninth, the <em>Vita Merlini</em>, is the great exception, keeping barely half the functions and inverting the rest (the hero flees instead of questing, his lack is his own mind, his cure is given not won, his reward refused). The variations in the lower section are where each poem's individual project surfaces. Manawydan is the cleanest fit to the spine; Math is its opposite — it keeps the pieces but redistributes them, with Villainy multiplied across four villains, Punishment run twice, and the hero split between a passive protagonist and the trickster who is villain and redeemer at once.",
  propp: [
    { sym: "α", name: "Initial situation", culhwch: "present", pwyll: "present", gawain: "present", orfeo: "present", owain: "present", branwen: "present",
      manawydan: "present",
      math: "present",
      vitamerlini: "present",
      gloss: "All eight poems open by introducing the court and family — Cilydd & Goleuddydd, Pwyll's Arberth, Owain's Caerleon, Arthur's Camelot, Orfeo's Winchester, and Branwen's House of Llŷr on the rock of Harlech." },
    { sym: "A", name: "Villainy (Lack)", culhwch: "present", pwyll: "present", gawain: "present", orfeo: "present", owain: "present", branwen: "present",
      manawydan: "present",
      math: "present",
      vitamerlini: "present",
      gloss: "Culhwch: the stepmother's curse. Pwyll: the courtesy debt at Glyn Cuch (and later Gwawl's claim, and later the lost son — three lacks in one tale). Gawain: the Green Knight's challenge. Orfeo: the abduction. Branwen: Efnisien's outrage on Matholwch's horses, the villainy that poisons the alliance. Each opens a lack that the rest fills." },
    { sym: "B", name: "Mediation / dispatch", culhwch: "present", pwyll: "present", gawain: "present", orfeo: "present", owain: "present", branwen: "present",
      manawydan: "present",
      math: "present",
      vitamerlini: "present",
      gloss: "Culhwch dispatched by his father; Pwyll dispatched by Arawn; Gawain dispatches himself (steps from the table); Orfeo dispatches himself (abdication speech). The Welsh tales have true mediation (a figure speaking the call); the English tales have self-mediation; and Branwen has the smallest mediator of all — a hand-reared starling carrying a letter across the sea." },
    { sym: "C", name: "Counteraction begins", culhwch: "present", pwyll: "present", gawain: "present", orfeo: "present", owain: "present", branwen: "present",
      manawydan: "present",
      math: "present",
      vitamerlini: "minimal",
      gloss: "All eight heroes accept the call. In Gawain instant (the axe-taking); in Culhwch deliberative; in Pwyll instant and pragmatic (the year-exchange handshake); in Owain stung into it by Cei’s mockery and Cynon’s tale; in Orfeo after ten years of grief; in Branwen the instant Branwen’s letter reaches Brân." },
    { sym: "↑", name: "Departure", culhwch: "present", pwyll: "present", gawain: "present", orfeo: "present", owain: "present", branwen: "present",
      manawydan: "present",
      math: "present",
      vitamerlini: "inverted",
      gloss: "All eight: the hero leaves home. Pwyll departs for Annwn (and Teirnon later for Arberth — a doubled departure); Owain departs twice too, first secretly for the fountain, then mad into the wilderness; and Brân wades the sea to Ireland." },
    { sym: "D", name: "Donor's first function", culhwch: "present", pwyll: "present", gawain: "present", orfeo: "present", owain: "present", branwen: "present",
      manawydan: "inverted",
      math: "present",
      vitamerlini: "present",
      gloss: "Culhwch: the six extraordinary companions are themselves the agents. Pwyll: Arawn IS the donor (and later Rhiannon is donor of the bag). Gawain: Bertilak's bargain. Orfeo: the Fairy King's rash boon. Strikingly often, the donor and the antagonist are the same figure — and Branwen inverts the function outright: Brân is donor of the Cauldron of Rebirth, but gives it to the enemy as amends. Manawydan inverts it differently — the donor-slot holds a trap, the golden bowl that should be an aid and is a snare; the hero receives no helper and no gift at all (see F)." },
    { sym: "F", name: "Receipt of magical agent", culhwch: "present", pwyll: "present", gawain: "present", orfeo: "present", owain: "present", branwen: "present",
      manawydan: "absent",
      math: "present",
      vitamerlini: "present",
      gloss: "Culhwch: the companions. Pwyll: Arawn's form (a body to wear for a year), and later Rhiannon's never-filling bag. Gawain: the green girdle. Orfeo: the harp. Each tale's agent is its central object — a band, a body and a bag, a sash, an instrument, and (in Branwen) a cauldron — though Branwen’s agent is handed to the enemy and turns against its giver. Manawydan is the pointed exception: its hero receives no magical agent whatever and lifts a kingdom-wide enchantment with none — only patience, a glove and a refusal to be shamed. The corpus's one wholly un-magical hero." },
    { sym: "G", name: "Guidance to the goal", culhwch: "present", pwyll: "present", gawain: "present", orfeo: "present", owain: "present", branwen: "present",
      manawydan: "present",
      math: "present",
      vitamerlini: "present",
      gloss: "Culhwch: Cynddylig the never-lost guide. Pwyll: Arawn brings him to Annwn's boundary; Rhiannon brings him to her father's court. Gawain: the Wirral road. Orfeo: the hawking ladies. Branwen: Brân lays his own body as a bridge for the host to cross the Llinon." },
    { sym: "H", name: "Struggle", culhwch: "present", pwyll: "present", gawain: "present", orfeo: "present", owain: "present", branwen: "present",
      manawydan: "present",
      math: "present",
      vitamerlini: "absent",
      gloss: "Culhwch: combat (the boar hunt, the Black Witch). Pwyll: the duel at the ford with Hafgan; later the bag-trick at the feast. Gawain: standing still under the axe. Orfeo: a verbal contest of speech-acts. Six forms of contest — combat, duel, endurance, rhetoric, Branwen’s pitched battle in the hall, and Manawydan’s bargain over a mouse, the only struggle in the corpus won with no blow struck." },
    { sym: "J", name: "Victory", culhwch: "present", pwyll: "present", gawain: "present", orfeo: "present", owain: "present", branwen: "present",
      manawydan: "present",
      math: "present",
      vitamerlini: "absent",
      gloss: "Culhwch: boar driven into the sea; Witch beheaded. Pwyll: Hafgan defeated with one stroke; Gwawl bagged. Gawain: he survives the axe. Orfeo: the Fairy King yields by his own word. Branwen: the field is won — but pyrrhically, at the cost of all but seven." },
    { sym: "K", name: "Liquidation of lack", culhwch: "present", pwyll: "present", gawain: "present", orfeo: "present", owain: "present", branwen: "present",
      manawydan: "present",
      math: "present",
      vitamerlini: "present",
      gloss: "Culhwch: the treasures and the bride won. Pwyll: Annwn restored, Rhiannon won, Pryderi recovered (each of his three lacks resolved on its own arc). Gawain: the bargain discharged. Orfeo: Heurodis recovered. Branwen: the lack is ‘liquidated’ into catastrophe — Branwen freed, both kingdoms emptied. Manawydan is the bright opposite: the captives freed, the enchantment lifted, the wasteland made whole — the one clean, complete liquidation in the corpus." },
    { sym: "ε", name: "Reconnaissance", culhwch: "absent", pwyll: "minimal", gawain: "present", orfeo: "present", owain: "present", branwen: "present",
      manawydan: "present",
      math: "present",
      vitamerlini: "absent",
      gloss: "Gawain and Orfeo have full scouting beats (the Green Knight's hall-survey, the two armed knights in Heurodis's vision). Pwyll has minimal reconnaissance — Arawn knows Pwyll's name before speaking, Teirnon recognises Pwyll's face in the child. Culhwch has no proper reconnaissance at all. Branwen: the Irish swineherds spy Brân’s host crossing the sea — the riddle of the moving forest and mountain." },
    { sym: "η", name: "Trickery", culhwch: "absent", pwyll: "present", gawain: "present", orfeo: "minimal", owain: "present", branwen: "present",
      manawydan: "present",
      math: "present",
      vitamerlini: "present",
      gloss: "Gawain is BUILT on trickery (the Green Knight's bluff, the exchange-of-winnings, the lady's wooing) — and Math rivals it: Gwydion's whole career is fraud and illusion (the swine-exchange, the wren-name, the phantom fleet). Pwyll uses trickery on the hero's side: the beggar-disguise and the never-filling bag that trap Gwawl. Orfeo's minstrel-disguise is sincere as far as it goes. Culhwch has no scheming at all. Branwen: the false peace — the house built to honour Brân, with two hundred armed men hidden in meal-bags." },
    { sym: "M", name: "Difficult task", culhwch: "present", pwyll: "minimal", gawain: "present", orfeo: "inverted", owain: "present", branwen: "absent",
      manawydan: "absent",
      math: "absent",
      vitamerlini: "present",
      gloss: "Culhwch: the ~40 anoethau. Gawain: the temptation triptych. Pwyll: minimal — the chaste-bed beat is a single discrete task, not a catalogue. Orfeo: the hero tests the steward (M inverted — the hero sets the test rather than receiving it). Five registers of the same beat: list, triptych, vow, inversion — and Owain’s repeatable ordeal of the fountain-combat. Branwen, Manawydan and Math have none: no task is set their heroes. Branwen's engine is alliance and betrayal; Manawydan's is endurance and a bargain; Math's is trickery and transformation — nothing in any of the three must be fetched or killed by a quest." },
    { sym: "↓", name: "Return", culhwch: "absent", pwyll: "present", gawain: "present", orfeo: "present", owain: "present", branwen: "present",
      manawydan: "present",
      math: "present",
      vitamerlini: "present",
      gloss: "Culhwch stays at the wedding feast — no return arc. Pwyll returns from Annwn to Dyfed; later Teirnon brings the child to Arberth; later Pwyll returns to a court missing his queen. Gawain rides back to Camelot. Orfeo walks back to Winchester. Pwyll has the most layered return-structure of the eight (Owain returns twice: from the fountain-realm, and from madness; Manawydan's captives return from the vanished caer; and Lleu returns from being an eagle); Branwen’s is the darkest — the seven bring Brân’s head home from a feast out of time, but Branwen dies on the way." },
    { sym: "o", name: "Unrecognised arrival", culhwch: "absent", pwyll: "present", gawain: "absent", orfeo: "present", owain: "present", branwen: "absent",
      manawydan: "present",
      math: "present",
      vitamerlini: "absent",
      gloss: "Pwyll, Orfeo and Owain all carry the unrecognised-arrival motif (Owain fights the long duel and defends Luned unrecognised, in a borrowed name). Pwyll arrives at Gwawl's feast in heavy old rags asking for a bag's-worth of food; Orfeo arrives at Winchester as a wandering harper. Three Insular instances of the Odyssean shape; Branwen has no disguised-arrival beat. Manawydan inverts the figure — here it is the villain, Llwyd, who arrives unrecognised (thrice, as scholar, priest and bishop), the disguised stranger working against the hero rather than the hero in disguise." },
    { sym: "Q", name: "Recognition", culhwch: "present", pwyll: "present", gawain: "present", orfeo: "present", owain: "present", branwen: "absent",
      manawydan: "present",
      math: "present",
      vitamerlini: "minimal",
      gloss: "Each poem has its recognition scene. Pwyll has the most decisive: Teirnon looks at the boy he raised and sees Pwyll's face — recognition by resemblance. Goreu beheads Ysbaddaden; Bertilak reveals himself to Gawain; Orfeo reveals himself to the steward in the conditional. Branwen has no recognition-of-the-hero scene. Manawydan's recognition is of the villain instead — the disguised bishop forced to name himself Llwyd son of Cil Coed, and his whole hidden cause exposed." },
    { sym: "T", name: "Transfiguration", culhwch: "present", pwyll: "present", gawain: "present", orfeo: "present", owain: "present", branwen: "present",
      manawydan: "present",
      math: "present",
      vitamerlini: "present",
      gloss: "Culhwch wins his bride; Pwyll changes name to <em>Pen Annwn</em> after the year-exchange; Gawain dons the green sash; Orfeo is bathed, shaved, re-crowned; Brân is transfigured past death itself, into the undecayed, speaking Wondrous Head; and in Manawydan the wand turns the captive mouse back into the fairest of women and the wasteland blooms whole again. Math is the transfiguration-branch entire: men to beasts and back, a man to a wounded eagle and back, a woman to an owl, and a wife made from flowers — more shape-changing than the other seven together." },
    { sym: "W", name: "Wedding (or restoration)", culhwch: "present", pwyll: "present", gawain: "absent", orfeo: "present", owain: "present", branwen: "absent",
      manawydan: "present",
      math: "present",
      vitamerlini: "inverted",
      gloss: "Culhwch closes on a wedding; Pwyll closes on a married couple, a recovered son, and an heir secured (a triple restoration); Orfeo closes on a re-coronation of a still-married couple. Two tales refuse the close, oppositely. Gawain declines an offered wedding (Bertilak invites; he goes home alone). Branwen instead OPENS on a wedding and spends the whole branch undoing it, closing not on a union but on graves on the Alaw and a head in the ground. Manawydan opens on a wedding too — Manawydan and Rhiannon, in its first movement — but, unlike Branwen, makes good on it: the function is fulfilled as restoration, the marriage surviving the wasteland and the land made whole around it. The declined union (Gawain), the destroyed one (Branwen), the one carried through to restoration (Manawydan), and the poisoned one (Math — a wedding reached mid-tale, the made wife betraying and unmade into an owl, the hero left ruling alone) — four fates of W." },
    { sym: "U", name: "Punishment of the villain", culhwch: "present", pwyll: "minimal", gawain: "absent", orfeo: "absent", owain: "present", branwen: "minimal",
      manawydan: "absent",
      math: "present",
      vitamerlini: "absent",
      gloss: "Culhwch ends with Goreu beheading Ysbaddaden — the fullest punishment; Owain kills the Black Knight, the giant and the two pages but spares and converts the Black Oppressor into a hospitaller, the corpus’s one redeemed antagonist. Pwyll punishes Gwawl partially (struck while in the bag) and then explicitly releases him on a sworn no-vengeance — a deliberate refusal of the full punishment-arc. Neither English poem punishes its antagonist at all. A clear gradient: Welsh tradition punishes, English tradition lets the antagonist persist as another kind of power; Pwyll sits between; and Branwen is a fourth case — its arch-villain Efnisien is punished by no one, but destroys himself in a single redeeming act, bursting the cauldron with his own body. And Manawydan is a fifth case — punishment deliberately refused: holding the enchanter's wife and every card, Manawydan spares Llwyd and takes guarantees instead of vengeance, the bright counterpart to Pwyll's release of the bagged Gwawl and the move that ends the revenge-cycle the First Branch began. Math is the opposite extreme — it punishes twice and exactly: the brothers three years as beasts, Blodeuwedd into an owl, Gronw by the return-blow he once dealt." },
    { sym: "I", name: "Branding", culhwch: "absent", pwyll: "absent", gawain: "present", orfeo: "absent", owain: "absent", branwen: "absent",
      manawydan: "absent",
      math: "absent",
      vitamerlini: "absent",
      gloss: "Gawain alone carries a wound back. The others return unmarked — Culhwch was always the catalyst, not the doer; Pwyll is restored to his own body without a sign; Orfeo's beard and rags are washed off. Branwen leaves no victory-brand either; what the seven carry home is not a wound but a head." },
    { sym: "Pr Rs", name: "Pursuit & Rescue", culhwch: "absent", pwyll: "absent", gawain: "absent", orfeo: "absent", owain: "present", branwen: "absent",
      manawydan: "absent",
      math: "absent",
      vitamerlini: "present",
      gloss: "Seven of the eight refuse the chase — but Owain breaks the pattern: it pursues the fleeing Black Knight headlong into the castle (the portcullis shears Owain’s horse in two behind the saddle), and its whole back half is a chain of rescues. The one tale with a French twin is the one that uses Pursuit-and-Rescue; the other native tales (Culhwch, Pwyll, Branwen, Manawydan, Math) and the two English poems do not — Manawydan's rescue is a bargain on a hilltop, and Math's is a song sung to an eagle, neither a chase." },
    { sym: "L Ex", name: "False-hero / Exposure of impostor", culhwch: "absent", pwyll: "present", gawain: "absent", orfeo: "absent", owain: "minimal", branwen: "absent",
      manawydan: "minimal",
      math: "minimal",
      vitamerlini: "present",
      gloss: "Owain comes close, but Pwyll has the corpus’s only proper L/Ex pair — the six women lay a false claim against Rhiannon (L: false hero presents an unfounded claim); Teirnon's arrival with the boy exposes the claim (Ex). Neither English poem stages this; Culhwch never returns. The Insular wonder-tale's calumniated-wife pattern fires once, here. Branwen has its own suffering queen (persecuted, not falsely accused) but no false-hero/exposure pair. Manawydan and Math carry the Exposure half without the false-claim half — in Manawydan the disguised enchanter Llwyd is unmasked and confesses; in Math, Gwydion's illusions dissolve on schedule and the betrayers Blodeuwedd and Gronw are exposed in the reckoning — but in neither does an impostor ever press a claim to be answered." },
  ],

  archetypeIntro: "Six character archetypes that recur across the nine poems, each filled by a different figure. The role-slots are remarkably consistent; what shifts is the moral occupant and the dramatic weight. The seventh row, the wrongfully accused, is the contribution of the Welsh tradition: Pwyll stages it as the calumniated wife (Rhiannon), Branwen as the persecuted queen of the Second Branch, and Owain as the condemned maid (Luned) — a figure the English pair refuse.",
  archetypes: [
    { role: "The hero",
      culhwch: { who: "Culhwch", note: "A king's son and Arthur's cousin; less a doer than a catalyst." },
      pwyll:   { who: "Pwyll (and Teirnon)", note: "Prince of Dyfed in Movements I–IV; in Movements V–VI the structural hero is Teirnon, who rescues the foal and recovers the boy. The tale runs two heroes in sequence." },
      gawain:  { who: "Sir Gawain", note: "Arthur's nephew; the pentangle-knight; the youngest at the high table." },
      orfeo:   { who: "Sir Orfeo", note: "King of Winchester; the harper before all other roles." },
      owain: { who: "Owain ab Urien", note: "Arthur\u2019s knight; the historical sixth-century king of Rheged refashioned as a romance hero \u2014 and the only hero of the eight who fails his central test (the broken term) and must win himself back through a chain of grateful rescues." },
      branwen: { who: "Bendigeidfran (Br\u00e2n)", note: "The giant king of the Island of the Mighty \u2014 less a quester than a sovereign and a sacrifice: he gives his sister to bind two islands, lays his own body as a bridge for his host, and at the last commands his own head struck off to become Britain\u2019s guardian talisman. The only hero of the corpus who does not survive his tale." },
      manawydan: { who: "Manawydan", note: "Son of Llŷr, brother of the dead giant-king Brân, rightful but un-aspiring king of Britain. The corpus's one wholly un-warlike, un-magical hero — he wins by patience, craft and an unbreakable bargain, not by sword, quest or spell." },
      math: { who: "Gwydion (and Lleu)", note: "Math splits the hero in two. Lleu Llaw Gyffes is the nominal hero but is acted upon for four movements — named, armed, wived, killed and restored, all by others — and acts for himself only at the very end. The real agency belongs to Gwydion, the trickster-magician who is the branch's villain in the first movement and its redeemer in the last: the one who does, beside the one things are done to." },
      vitamerlini: { who: "Merlin", note: "King and prophet of the Demetae, unmade by grief into the wild man of the woods — the corpus's one hero whose quest is wholly inward (to recover his own lost mind), and who, healed at last, refuses the throne for a hermit's peace." },
      gloss: "Each tale's hero is a king or king-adjacent young man. Pwyll is unique in fielding two heroes in succession — the young prince of the first half is replaced by the kindly older lord of the second. Only Orfeo is the king in his own right, and only Orfeo's hero brings the magical agent (the harp) with him; Pwyll, Culhwch and Gawain each receive theirs. Branwen’s Brân is the only hero who does not survive his tale — a king who ends as a guardian head." },

    { role: "The taken / the goal",
      culhwch: { who: "Olwen", note: "Daughter of Ysbaddaden; coaches Culhwch to out-promise her father." },
      pwyll:   { who: "Rhiannon (and Pryderi)", note: "Rhiannon as bride-on-the-horse, won by asking; Pryderi as stolen infant recovered after seven years. Two goals across the tale's two halves — a queen, then a son." },
      gawain:  { who: "—", note: "No taken figure; the lack is moral, not personal." },
      orfeo:   { who: "Heurodis", note: "Queen abducted into Faerie at noon under the ympe-tree; speaks twice in the whole poem." },
      owain: { who: "The Countess of the Fountain", note: "Won by combat-and-wit in the first half, lost by the broken term, regained in the last line. Like Pwyll\u2019s Rhiannon, a goal across two halves \u2014 but here lost through the hero\u2019s own fault, not stolen." },
      branwen: { who: "Branwen", note: "Not taken but given \u2014 married across the sea to bind two islands, then scapegoated, driven to the kitchen and beaten daily. Her wrong, carried home by the starling, is the lack the whole expedition sets out to right; she dies of grief on the return. The goal-figure as victim rather than prize." },
      manawydan: { who: "Pryderi and Rhiannon", note: "Both taken at once in the caer — held fast to the golden bowl, struck dumb, carried off with the vanishing fort — and both the goal the whole back half labours to recover. The First Branch's doubled goal (Rhiannon won, Pryderi recovered) taken together and won back together in the Third." },
      math: { who: "Lleu (lost as an eagle)", note: "The goal is the hero himself: speared and transformed, Lleu flies off as a wounded eagle and roosts dying in an oak, and the last movement is Gwydion's search to find and recover him. The taken-and-recovered figure turned inward — the protagonist as his own lost goal." },
      vitamerlini: { who: "Arthur (borne to Avalon); Merlin's own reason", note: "The role doubles: Arthur is the one taken over the sea to the Isle of Apples to be healed — the taken who does <em>not</em> return — while the deeper goal is Merlin's own lost mind, the inward thing the whole tale strains to recover." },
      gloss: "Seven of the eight have a goal-figure; Gawain alone refuses one. Branwen’s is the goal as victim — given, scapegoated, and dead of grief, not a prize won. Pwyll has a doubled goal — Rhiannon won-by-asking and Pryderi recovered-by-recognition. Olwen is prize-by-quest; Heurodis is prize-by-recovery; the Countess of the Fountain is prize-by-combat lost-by-fault and regained; Rhiannon is both, across the two halves of her tale." },

    { role: "The Otherworld king (antagonist who is also host)",
      culhwch: { who: "Ysbaddaden Bencawr", note: "Chief of Giants; fated to die when his daughter weds; sets the impossible tasks." },
      pwyll:   { who: "Arawn (with Hafgan)", note: "Arawn IS the host — courteous, kingly, fair-dealing. The antagonism is structural (Pwyll owes him courtesy-debt) not moral. Hafgan stands in for the absent antagonist; Arawn keeps his throne, his queen, and his friendship with Pwyll." },
      gawain:  { who: "Bertilak / the Green Knight", note: "Antagonist, host, and donor fused in one figure. Bound to honour, but bound." },
      orfeo:   { who: "The Fairy King", note: "Otherworld king of his own kingdom. Bound by his own word; not punished, only constrained." },
      owain: { who: "The Black Knight / the Du Traws", note: "Owain SPLITS the fused role the others combine: the Black Knight is pure antagonist (no host-courtesy), the yellow lord pure host (no menace). The fusion returns only at the end, darkly, in the Black Oppressor \u2014 the murderous host whose welcome is a trap." },
      branwen: { who: "Matholwch", note: "Host and husband, not Otherworld lord: he weds Branwen at Aberffraw and receives the cauldron, but, too weak to hold his court, lets her be abused and is governed to war. Antagonist by weakness, not malice \u2014 the corpus\u2019s true engine of ruin works inside Br\u00e2n\u2019s own house, in Efnisien." },
      manawydan: { who: "Llwyd (antagonist only; no host)", note: "Manawydan splits the fused role even more sharply than Owain: its Otherworld has no court and no host at all — only an empty trap-fort — so the antagonist half stands alone in Llwyd, the hidden enchanter who never plays host except as a lying disguise (the bishop). The 'host' half of the archetype is simply absent." },
      math: { who: "— (villainy distributed; no host)", note: "Math dissolves the role entirely: there is no Otherworld-court host, and the villainy is shared among four distinct figures across the branch — Gwydion (the fraud and the war), Aranrhod (the curses), and Blodeuwedd with Gronw (the murder). The single antagonist-host of the genre is split four ways, and the worst of them, Gwydion, becomes the hero." },
      vitamerlini: { who: "Morgen of the Isle of Apples", note: "The Otherworld sovereign as healer and host, not antagonist: Morgen, chief of the nine sisters, who receives the wounded Arthur as physician. The benign face of the role Arawn and the Fairy King play darker elsewhere." },
      gloss: "Every tale has a figure who is at once antagonist and host. Culhwch's is a doomed giant; Gawain's is a fused triple-role; Orfeo's is a king who keeps his throne; Pwyll's is the only one who becomes a friend. Five theologies of the antagonist — and Pwyll the only one that ends in alliance; Branwen adds Matholwch, antagonist by weakness, a host and husband governed to war while the true ruin works inside Brân’s own house; and Math dissolves the role altogether — no Otherworld host at all, the villainy split among four hands." },

    { role: "The powers behind",
      culhwch: { who: "The stepmother (sets the geis)", note: "Lays the destiny on Culhwch out of spite; never reappears." },
      pwyll:   { who: "(unseen) — the foal-and-baby thief", note: "The hand that reaches through Teirnon's window for the foal — and presumably the same power that steals Pryderi from Arberth on May-eve — is never named or shown. Only its severed arm remains. Pwyll alone has an antagonist that is structural rather than dramatised." },
      gawain:  { who: "Morgan le Fay", note: "Off-stage prime mover of the whole test; in age-disguise at the castle; named at the reveal." },
      orfeo:   { who: "(none)", note: "The Fairy King acts on his own behalf; no off-stage mover." },
      owain: { who: "(none off-stage) \u2014 Luned, on-stage", note: "Owain, like Orfeo, has no off-stage mover; its plot-engine is Luned, who works the marriage from within the story. The darogan (prophecy) that Owain would subdue the Black Oppressor is the one hint of a fate-power, and it too is spoken on-stage." },
      branwen: { who: "Efnisien (on-stage)", note: "Branwen, like Owain and Orfeo, has no off-stage mover: its engine of ruin is Efnisien the strife-maker, working in full view \u2014 mutilating the horses, reading and crushing the meal-bag ambush, casting the child into the fire, and at the last bursting the cauldron with his own body. The \u2018power behind\u2019 made visible and flesh." },
      manawydan: { who: "Llwyd son of Cil Coed", note: "Manawydan's great structural surprise: unlike Branwen, Owain and Orfeo, it DOES have a hidden off-stage mover — Llwyd, who lays the whole enchantment out of friendship for Gwawl and works wholly unseen until forced to name himself at the gallows. The role Gawain gives Morgan and Culhwch the stepmother, here a male magician avenging a generation-old grudge from the First Branch." },
      math: { who: "Aranrhod", note: "The cold mother who lays the three destiny-curses on her own son and then recedes — the power that shapes the whole middle of the branch by spoken word (tynged), exactly as Culhwch's stepmother and Gawain's Morgan do. And like them she is a goddess-figure: Aranrhod survives in the star-name Caer Arianrhod, restoring the demoted-goddess-as-schemer pattern." },
      vitamerlini: { who: "Taliesin, and the stars", note: "Not plotters but knowledge itself — Taliesin's natural philosophy and the wheeling stars Merlin reads. The power behind this tale is a legible cosmos, not a hidden hand." },
      gloss: "Four of the eight have a named figure behind the figure (the stepmother, Morgan, Llwyd and Aranrhod — three working by spoken destiny, and, in Manawydan, a male magician working by enchantment). Pwyll has the figure but refuses to name it; Orfeo and Owain refuse the whole role (Owain’s engine, Luned, works in full view). The Welsh and English traditions converge on the demoted-goddess-as-schemer where they don't simply refuse the layer; Branwen, like Owain and Orfeo, refuses the off-stage role — its engine, Efnisien, works the ruin in full view." },

    { role: "The threshold helper",
      culhwch: { who: "Custennin & his wife", note: "Fire-breathing herdsman and Culhwch's aunt; warn the company; hide Goreu in a stone chest." },
      pwyll:   { who: "Teirnon Twrf Liant", note: "Lord of Gwent Is-Coed; raises the lost child as his own son for seven years; recognises Pwyll's face in the boy and brings him back. The keeper-of-the-lost-child, the most active threshold-helper in the corpus." },
      gawain:  { who: "Mary on the inside of the shield", note: "Patroness summoned in the Christmas Eve prayer; the castle appears in answer." },
      orfeo:   { who: "The Winchester beggar", note: "Houses Orfeo and Heurodis at the town's edge; lends the disguise; quiet hub of the recognition." },
      owain: { who: "Luned (and the keeper of beasts)", note: "Luned gives the ring that frees Owain from the portcullis-trap and contrives his marriage; the keeper of beasts directs the road to the fountain. After Teirnon, the most consequential threshold-helper in the corpus \u2014 she does not merely shelter the hero, she remakes his life twice." },
      branwen: { who: "The starling", note: "Branwen fills the threshold-helper slot with a bird: the starling she rears and teaches at her kneading-trough carries her letter across the sea and brings the host of Britain. The smallest helper in the corpus, turning the largest wheel." },
      manawydan: { who: "— (none; Cigfa counsels but turns no wheel)", note: "Manawydan has no threshold-helper: the dispossessed king is his own resource, and lifts the enchantment alone. The nearest figure is his steadfast companion Cigfa, who shares the wilderness and counsels caution over the mouse — but she opens no door and turns no wheel. The role the other tales fill with an elder, a saint, a beggar or a clever maid stands empty." },
      math: { who: "The bondman's sow (and his house)", note: "Math fills the slot, like Branwen, with an animal: the bondman of Maenor Bennardd shelters the searching Gwydion, and it is his sow — slipping off each morning by a road no one can follow — that leads Gwydion to the oak and the wounded eagle. The humblest of guides turning the wheel of the whole recovery." },
      vitamerlini: { who: "The harper-messenger (and Ganieda)", note: "The harper who climbs into the wild and, with the cithara, draws Merlin back across the threshold from madness to reason; dispatched and seconded throughout by Ganieda." },
      gloss: "An aged or marginal figure at the threshold turns the wheel in seven of the eight (Manawydan alone has none) (in Owain, the quick-witted Luned and the monstrous keeper of beasts). Teirnon is the most dramatic of them — he doesn't merely warn or shelter, he keeps the lost prince's body for years. Each tradition draws on what is available to it: Welsh kin-network (Culhwch, Pwyll), English Marian piety (Gawain), English roadside almsgiving (Orfeo); and, in Branwen, a bird — the starling that carries the queen’s word across the sea; and, in Math, a beast — the sow that leads Gwydion to the wounded eagle." },

    { role: "The faithful one (rewarded)",
      culhwch: { who: "Goreu the avenger", note: "Hidden in the stone chest by his mother; emerges to behead Ysbaddaden and take the giant's lands." },
      pwyll:   { who: "Pryderi (and the Dyfed nobles)", note: "Pryderi as the recovered son who succeeds Pwyll and inherits the seven cantref of Dyfed (and later three more, and then four more). The Dyfed nobles who waited a year while Arawn ruled in Pwyll's body are tacitly rewarded with the king they had thought they had." },
      gawain:  { who: "—", note: "No faithful retainer figure in the same sense; the court itself adopts the green sash but no individual is singled out for reward." },
      orfeo:   { who: "The high steward", note: "Holds the kingdom honestly for ten years; tested by the lying tale; rewarded with the throne after Orfeo's day." },
      owain: { who: "Luned and the lion", note: "Two faithful figures: Luned, who stakes her freedom on Owain\u2019s worth and is saved at the stake; and the lion, loyalty made flesh, who fills the faithful-retainer slot with a beast. Owain is the only tale to put an animal in this role." },
      branwen: { who: "\u2014 (none rewarded)", note: "Branwen, like Gawain, has no rewarded faithful figure \u2014 but for the opposite reason: the faithful (Branwen herself, the seven survivors, even Efnisien\u2019s redeeming death) are not rewarded but bereaved, because there is no restored order to reward into, only graves and a buried head." },
      manawydan: { who: "Cigfa, and the restored house", note: "Manawydan rewards all its faithful: Cigfa, who kept faith with Manawydan through the wilderness, and the freed Pryderi and Rhiannon, restored with the whole kingdom around them. Where Branwen's faithful are bereaved, Manawydan's are made whole — the clean restoration the corpus elsewhere reserves for its quest-tales." },
      math: { who: "Goewin, raised to queen", note: "Math's reward is amends to the wronged: the violated foot-holder Goewin is married by the king and given authority over the whole realm, before any thought of punishing the offenders. A reward that doubles as justice — the faithful-one slot filled by the wronged-one made queen." },
      vitamerlini: { who: "Ganieda", note: "The sister who never gives up on her brother and at the last inherits his prophetic gift — faith rewarded not with land or marriage but with the seer's mantle itself." },
      gloss: "Six of the eight close on the reward of a faithful figure (Goreu inherits the giant's lands, Pryderi inherits Pwyll's, the steward inherits Orfeo's, and Owain's Luned — with the lion — is saved and vindicated). Gawain alone has no equivalent. The tales that walk back to a court reward the faithful one; the tale that does not return offers no reward. Branwen, like Gawain, offers none — but here because there is no restored order to reward into, only graves and a buried head." },

    { role: "The wrongfully accused (the Welsh romances)",
      culhwch: { who: "—", note: "No accused figure; the tale's moral vector is straightforward." },
      pwyll:   { who: "Rhiannon", note: "Falsely accused of killing her son by six terrified attendants; refuses to denounce them; accepts her penance at the gate for seven years rather than abandon her marriage. Exonerated by Teirnon's evidence. The corpus's only proper calumniated-wife arc." },
      gawain:  { who: "—", note: "No accused figure; the test runs at the host's castle, not in court." },
      orfeo:   { who: "—", note: "Heurodis is taken, not accused; she vanishes from the poem until the rescue." },
      owain: { who: "Luned", note: "Condemned to burn for vouching that Owain was no deceiver \u2014 wrongfully accused and sentenced to death, rescued at the last hour. The pattern Pwyll gives to the wife (Rhiannon), Owain gives to the maid (Luned): the two Welsh romances share the figure the English pair refuse." },
      branwen: { who: "Branwen (persecuted, not accused)", note: "The Second Branch\u2019s suffering queen \u2014 not calumniated like her First-Branch sister Rhiannon but scapegoated: punished in the kitchen for Efnisien\u2019s offence, struck daily, the blow remembered as one of the Three Unhappy Blows of Britain. The Mabinogi stages the persecuted queen in both its first two branches." },
      manawydan: { who: "— (none)", note: "No accused or condemned figure: the wrong in the Third Branch is done to a whole land by enchantment, not to a woman by calumny. Rhiannon, the First Branch's calumniated wife, returns here — but is taken, not accused." },
      math: { who: "— (none)", note: "No wrongly-accused figure: the branch's wronged woman, Goewin, is violated rather than calumniated, and its other women are a curser (Aranrhod) and a genuinely guilty wife (Blodeuwedd). Math joins Manawydan as the two Branches that leave the slot empty." },
      vitamerlini: { who: "Ganieda (by the leaf in her hair)", note: "Accused of adultery by the leaf Merlin's laugh exposes, Ganieda alone among the corpus's accused women clears herself not by endurance (like Rhiannon or Branwen) but by counter-cunning — discrediting the very prophet who named her." },
      gloss: "The two Welsh romances stage a wrongly-condemned woman where the English pair do not: Pwyll the calumniated wife (Rhiannon, accused of infanticide, penanced at the gate), Owain the condemned maid (Luned, sentenced to burn for vouching that Owain was no deceiver). The distinctively Welsh contribution to the archetype grid — staged in three of the Welsh tales (Rhiannon the calumniated wife, Branwen the persecuted queen, Luned the condemned maid) and left empty by the other three (Culhwch, Manawydan, Math) and by the English pair." },
  ],

  /* ── The axis of desire (Greimas), laid across all eight ───────────────── */
  desireAxis: {
    intro: "Two analytical layers were added to every tale after the original five: <strong>Desire</strong> (Greimas's actantial model — the functional structure of <em>wanting</em>) and <strong>Theme</strong> (the Parry–Lord oral type-scenes). Here is the desire layer read across the corpus: each tale's Subject, the Object it wants, the Opponent that blocks it, and the finding the lens exists to surface — <strong>does the arrow of desire reach its Object?</strong> Eight of the nine reach; <strong>Branwen alone falls short</strong> (its arrow is drawn dashed in the tale's own diagram), Gawain reaches only with a flaw, and the <em>Vita Merlini</em> reaches the strangest Object of all — the hero's own lost mind.",
    rows: [
      { tale: "culhwch", subject: "Culhwch", object: "Olwen, won for his wife", opponent: "Ysbaddaden Bencawr", reaches: true, verdict: "reached — but by Arthur's band, not the near-passive Subject; the Object (Olwen) doubles as a Helper, coaching him to win her" },
      { tale: "pwyll", subject: "Pwyll → Teirnon", object: "Rhiannon won, and an heir to follow", opponent: "Gwawl, then the unseen power", reaches: true, verdict: "reached — uniquely, by two Subjects in succession; the Opponent doubles to match" },
      { tale: "branwen", subject: "Bendigeidfran", object: "Branwen freed, the alliance restored", opponent: "the insult, and the Cauldron of Rebirth", reaches: false, verdict: "the arrow falls short — Branwen is freed but both islands are wasted; the rescue is the ruin. Efnisien is both Opponent and Helper" },
      { tale: "manawydan", subject: "Manawydan", object: "the enchantment lifted; the taken freed", opponent: "Llwyd son of Cil Coed", reaches: true, verdict: "reached — by no blow at all; the Helper is the Opponent's own wife, the slow mouse" },
      { tale: "math", subject: "Gwydion", object: "Lleu made a man, and restored", opponent: "Aranrhod's curses, then Gronw", reaches: true, verdict: "reached — but every actant wears two faces: Aranrhod is Sender and Opponent; Blodeuwedd a Helper who turns Opponent" },
      { tale: "owain", subject: "Owain", object: "the Lady of the Fountain", opponent: "the Black Knight, then his own broken word", reaches: true, verdict: "reached twice — won, lost by his own fault, won back; the Opponent doubles inward to his faithlessness" },
      { tale: "orfeo", subject: "Orfeo", object: "Heurodis, recovered from Faerie", opponent: "the Fairy King", reaches: true, verdict: "reached — won by art, not force; the only hero whose sole Helper is a magical agent he carries himself (the harp)" },
      { tale: "gawain", subject: "Gawain", object: "his honour kept whole (and his life)", opponent: "the Green Knight, and his own instinct to live", reaches: true, verdict: "reached, but flawed — the nick at the neck is the exact gap between the desire and its Object; the girdle is a Helper that is also the wound" },
      { tale: "vitamerlini", subject: "Merlin", object: "his own lost reason — an ordinary mind, to be \"given back to himself\"", opponent: "his own madness, and the prophetic gift that \"denied the mind its natural rest\"", reaches: true, verdict: "reached — the corpus's one wholly inward quest: Subject, Object and Receiver are one man; the cure is given by a spring, not won; and the Opponent he escapes turns out to be the very gift he lays down" },
    ],
    finding: "The pattern the apparatus surfaces: the wonder-tales drive their hero's arrow home (Culhwch, Pwyll, Manawydan, Math, Owain, Orfeo), the chivalric honour-test lets it reach but with a flaw (Gawain), and the one tragedy bends it into a wheel — <em>Branwen</em>, where the want and the wasting are the same motion. The <em>Vita Merlini</em> stands apart from them all: its arrow flies not outward to a bride or a kingdom but <em>inward</em>, the only tale whose hero wants nothing but to be himself again — and reaches it, by the gift of a spring.",
  },

  /* ── Shared type-scenes (Parry–Lord), tales as columns ─────────────────── */
  themesIntro: "The oral type-scenes — the set-pieces a singer composes with, larger than a motif and smaller than the tale — identified in the real text and laid across the nine. The <strong>feast is universal</strong>; the rest cluster by tradition and tale (the council is a Welsh-cluster set-piece; the mound belongs to Branwen alone, and the sea-road she now shares with the Vita Merlini’s voyage to Avalon). Each cell links into its Read passage via the per-tale Theme layer.",
  themes: [
    { id: "feast", code: "⟜", name: "the feast in hall",
      gawain: { passages: [1] }, culhwch: { passages: [7] }, orfeo: { passages: [5] }, pwyll: { passages: [4] }, branwen: { passages: [1] }, manawydan: { passages: [1] }, math: { passages: [1] }, owain: { passages: [1] }, vitamerlini: { passages: [3] },
      gloss: "The one universal set-piece: every tale stages a hall-feast — the boards, the cup, the seating by rank. Often the hinge (Pwyll's wedding-feast where the bag-trick springs; Gwydion's bardic feast at Pryderi's court; the wedding-feast Merlin invades on a stag) or the frame (Arthur's Caerleon, Rhydderch's hall)." },
    { id: "council", code: "⟜", name: "the council in hall",
      pwyll: { passages: [5] }, manawydan: { passages: [3] }, math: { passages: [3] }, owain: { passages: [5] }, vitamerlini: { passages: [14] },
      gloss: "The assembly type-scene — the folk in their orders, the matter laid in the middle. A Brittonic cluster: the men of Dyfed pressing for an heir, the craft-counsels of Manawydan, Math seeking a foot-holder, the Countess's people deciding on a champion — and the lords who gather to beg the healed Merlin to take up his sceptre again, and are refused." },
    { id: "lament", code: "⟜", name: "the lament",
      orfeo: { passages: [3] }, branwen: { passages: [6] }, owain: { passages: [7] }, vitamerlini: { passages: [1] },
      gloss: "The grief-cry over the irrevocable — and the corpus's darkest movements: Orfeo's ten years in the wastes, Branwen's keening on the Alaw, Owain's descent into madness among the deer, and Merlin's battlefield lament and winter cry to the wolf — the wild-man lament that is the very seed of his tale." },
    { id: "arming", code: "⟜", name: "the arming of the hero",
      gawain: { passages: [2] }, culhwch: { passages: [1] }, math: { passages: [4] },
      gloss: "The war-gear taken up in fixed order. Gawain's (ll. 566–669) is the corpus's purest; Culhwch's lavish setting-out opens his tale; and Math inverts it — Aranrhod, tricked, arms the very son she swore should bear no arms." },
    { id: "boast", code: "⟜", name: "the boast / catalogue",
      gawain: { passages: [3] }, culhwch: { passages: [2] },
      gloss: "Half the contest fought in words — and, in Culhwch, swollen into the great invocation-catalogue of Arthur's men (the extraordinary-companions, F601), the longest oral catalogue in the corpus. Gawain's is the exchange-of-winnings pact." },
    { id: "threshold", code: "⟜", name: "the crossing",
      orfeo: { passages: [4] }, owain: { passages: [2] }, vitamerlini: { passages: [12] },
      gloss: "The hero at the line between the worlds: Orfeo's rock-cleft into Faerie, Owain's storm-rite at the fountain, and Merlin's new-broken spring — the marked place by the water where he crosses back from madness to reason. The Otherworld answers at the marked place." },
    { id: "voyage", code: "⟜", name: "the sea-road",
      branwen: { passages: [4] }, vitamerlini: { passages: [9] },
      gloss: "The launching set-piece — keel to water, the salt road out of sight of land. Branwen has it as war (the host of Britain crossing to Ireland, the giant Brân wading the sea himself); the Vita has it as the otherworld-voyage — the ship bearing the wounded Arthur to the Isle of Apples, Barinthus at the helm." },
    { id: "mound", code: "⟜", name: "the raising of the mound",
      branwen: { passages: [6] },
      gloss: "The burial set-piece, the deeds laid in over the bones. Branwen alone closes on it — the grave on the Alaw, and the Wondrous Head buried at the White Hill to guard Britain." },
  ],
};
